Bottom Line: Enjoying this Costa Rica evokes the pleasures of walking into a bakery in winter alive with aromas of warming spices and rich cocoa.

Coffee Name: Colombia Granja La Esperanza Tres Dragones
Coffee Origin: Valle del Cauca growing region, Colombia
Bottom Line: A bombshell of a coffee with enough personality to stand up to a lemon tart — for breakfast, of course.
An exceptional Colombia cup with sweet and tart impulses in balance: deeply sweet florals and bright fruit notes throughout.
A deep yet delicate cup redolent with crisp fruit and spice-toned floral notes.
An exceptionally cleanly expressed natural-processed Burundi cup, citrus- and chocolate-toned.

Coffee Origin: Ka’u growing region, Big Island of Hawaii
Bottom Line: A complex, nuanced Ka’u coffee processed with a strain of wine yeast, encouraging a particularly vibrant, fruit-toned acidity.
A sweetly fermenty and chocolaty Colombia cup that invokes a rum-cordial-like combination of intense chocolate and fruity liqueur.
A balanced, sweetly savory DR Congo cup with dried fruit and chocolate notes throughout.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing district, Big Island of Hawaii
Bottom Line: A pretty, richly sweet Kona cup that leads with deep floral and nut tones.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Tarrazu Hacienda La Pradera
Bottom Line: A balanced washed process Costa Rica cup, lively, accessible, engaging.
A decidedly fruit-centered coffee with pleasing sweet ferment and rich chocolate notes throughout.
An unusual and compelling coffee: brisk but very sweet, with peach and deep, musky florals.
A pleasingly balanced cup, quiet, accessible and subtly original.
A fresh, sweet-toned cup: morning in a meadow.

Coffee Origin: Hambela Wamena District, Guji Zone, Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A lyrical washed-process Ethiopia cup: intricately balanced, complex, juicy, confident.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, Big Island of Hawaii
Bottom Line: A solid Kona cup that leads with nut tones and bright, yet accessible, acidity.
A roast-toned, sweetly chocolaty Peru cup with dried fruit and floral notes throughout.
An impeccably balanced, nuanced Tanzania cup that is an extraordinary value at $12 for 12 ounces.
A classic washed Yirgacheffe cup: bright, lively, redolent of stone fruit, citrus zest and cocoa.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: An inviting, rich-toned natural-processed Ethiopia cup with clear blueberry and chocolate notes and gentle acidity.
A robust, hearty Kenya, driven by sweet-pungent grapefruit and cedar, softened by dark chocolate suggestions.
Sweet flowers and intense sandalwood power this silky-bodied, fragrant Yirgacheffe.
A quietly original, resonant cup, exquisitely balanced and complete.
A deeply rich, big-bodied Kenya cup foregrounding spice notes, berries and bittersweet florals.
A solid Kenya cup: chocolaty, spice-toned, deeply sweet.
An accessible Geisha cup characterized by tropical fruit and cocoa notes throughout with intimations of honey-like florals.
A big-bodied Colombia driven by crisp chocolate and nut intrigue rounded by cherryish fruit.
A richly expressed, crisply bittersweet microlot from a tiny, woman-owned and operated farm in Peru.
A classic Ethiopia profile: cocoa- and citrus-toned. Given the distinction of the coffee, an outstanding value.
A friendly, straightforward washed Ethiopia cup with both organic and fair trade credentials.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A washed Sidamo cup with a developed roast profile that amplifies chocolate and floral notes; deeply and richly sweet throughout.
A deftly medium-roasted Colombia cup, balanced and satisfying in its familiar pleasures.
A straightforward, accessible Kenya cup with big chocolate notes as a throughline.
A darker-roasted Guatemala coffee that highlights pleasing cocoa and dried fruit notes.
A pleasing, balanced Honduras cup with pretty nut tones throughout.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: An easy-drinking natural-processed Ethiopia cup with ballast from spice-toned aromatic wood and florals.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A medium-roasted Ethiopia cup with pleasing cocoa and citrus notes throughout; wood-centered in the finish.
A good-value darker roasted Guatemala driven by quiet chocolate and nut notes.
A comfortingly familiar, darker roasted Colombia cup built around dark chocolate with undertones of vanilla-like florals.
A roast-prominent, cocoa-toned Colombia cup with an intriguing sweet-tart note.
A sweet though muted Guatemala cup: roasty cocoa and nut.
A good choice for those who like classic dark-roasted Sumatras: earthy-sweet, smoky chocolate.

Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, “Big Island” of Hawaii
Bottom Line: An aromatically complex, original cup that balances an enveloping sweetness with a quietly forceful pungency.
A striking cup from this rare variety: sweet, tart, rich, deep, and floral through and through.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Finca El Cerro Natural
Bottom Line: A resonantly fruit-forward, cocoa-toned natural-processed Pacamara cup, with high-toned florals and richly bittersweet citrus notes throughout.

Coffee Origin: Odo Shakiso District, Guji Zone, Oromia region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: An elegant, richly-layered single-farm Ethiopia cup. Natural processing develops sweet berry notes throughout.
An intriguing cup from the little-known coffee-producing region Madagascar: sweet, tart, balanced and inviting.
A richly sweet and fruit-forward Costa Rica cup with a developed roast profile that highlights chocolate and floral tones.
A high-toned, richly floral natural-processed Geisha cup from the famed Hacienda La Esmeralda farm in Boquete, Panama animated by crisp, citrusy fruit notes throughout.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia Region, south-central Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A deeply nuanced coffee with bittersweet citrus and sweet florals in front and ballast from rich chocolate and nougat.

A fruit- and floral-toned coffee from a lesser-known growing region on the Big Island of Hawai’i is worth seeking out for its balanced completeness and its suggestions of the tropics, both aromatically and in the cup.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Las Lajas Red Honey
Bottom Line: A sweet, multi-layered Costa Rica cup, its rich fruit amplified by skillful red honey processing.
A classically bright, floral-toned washed Ethiopia cup with added vivacity from stone fruit and citrus notes.
A balanced Colombia cup with notes of stonefruit and citrus on top and deep cocoa and rich aromatic wood underneath.
A Rwanda cup pleasingly balanced between sweet fruit and chocolate and rich aromatic wood.
Enjoy this straightforward Central America cup for its mild acidity and its sweet nut and deep floral notes.
An attractive choice for lovers of darker-roasted blends: sweet chocolate and flowers alongside dried fruit notes, with prominent smoky wood throughout.

A roast-forward blend that emphasizes chocolate and floral notes while developing the savory inclination of the green coffees as well: rich, musky, sweet. Might be particularly nice — apologies to purists — with a splash of milk.
An integrated, harmonious blend of washed- and natural-process coffees that highlights both sweet (blueberry) and tart (tamarind) fruits with big chocolate throughout.
A sweetly nutty and cocoa-toned cup with an especially buoyant mouthfeel.
An engaging, delicately spice-inflected blend pleasingly complicated by chocolate and citrus zest.

This coffee’s name is loosely drawn from the name of the winter solstice celebration for Mithraism, "Natalis Solis Invincti," which means “birthday of the unconquerable sun.” Drink it if for no other reason than this.
A friendly, balanced blend, equally sweet and tart, animated by a delicate cocoa.
An interesting blend skillfully dark-roasted, save for the bitter, burned finish. Otherwise, quietly intriguing, sweet and smoky.
A deeply sweet washed-process Ethiopia cup, spice-toned with elegant suggestions of dried stone fruit.
A balanced, sweet-savory Kenya cup with classic currant notes and a rich bittersweet undercurrent suggesting hop flowers throughout.
A deeply sweet Kenya with classic red berry notes, bittersweet florals, and minty herb notes.
A friendly, accessible Guatemala cup that leads with pleasing nut tones supported by spice-toned fruit. Gentle though expressive acidity.
An appealing blend of Costa Rica coffees that supports a local farmer’s collective: crisp, sweet and balanced.
A friendly, accessible Central America cup, crisply sweet with notes of stone fruit, cocoa and hazelnut.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Las Mercedes Pacamara Honey
Bottom Line: A deeply sweet Pacamara cup with savory undertones throughout, reminiscent of fine musk and marjoram-like sweet herbs.

Bottom Line: An exceptionally high-toned natural-processed Panama Geisha coffee with especially vibrant acidity, balanced structure, and deep floral notes throughout the profile.
An elegant, high-toned, washed-process Yirgacheffe cup saturated with floral and fruit notes throughout and a particularly engaging sweet-citrusy acidity.

An explosively sweet, fruit-forward natural-processed coffee produced by the same farm that gave us the latest price-record-breaking, most sought-after Geisha in the world. Consider this coffee a worthy and affordable cousin.

Coffee Name: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe GR1 Bedhatu Jibicho Washed
Bottom Line: A balanced, crisply herb-toned washed Yirgacheffe cup deepened by sweet stonefruit notes.
A balanced, cocoa-driven Kenya cup with classic currant notes and rich florals throughout.
A medium-roasted Kenya that highlights the coffee’s chocolate tendencies, with lively, high-toned acidity.

Coffee Origin: Mandheling growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia

A classic Kenya cup with bright, juicy fruit and lively sweet-tart acidity.
A straightforward, deeply sweet, cocoa-laden Guatemala cup.

Coffee Name: Washed Geisha Hacienda La Esmeralda Jaramillo Special
Bottom Line: A stunning, high-toned Geisha, downright majestic in the clarity of its aromatics and lyrical structure.

Coffee Name: Cordillera del Fuego Costa Rica Anaerobic
Bottom Line: A high-toned, cleanly fruit-forward Costa Rica cup with deeply rich savory underpinnings.

Coffee Name: Cordillera del Fuego Costa Rica Anaerobic
Bottom Line: An anaerobic-processed coffee whose startling originality leans toward musk, chocolate and cinnamon.

Deeply sweet in structure with savory undertones and intriguing, original aromatics centered on brisk, bittersweet flowers.
Drink it if you like a nuanced but bright, sweet-tart cup in the traditional style.
A big, juicy, and crisply sweet Kenya cup, with compelling savory undertones and a cocoa throughline.
An intensely bright coffee with attractive, savory-leaning undertones.
A friendly, accessible cocoa- and nut-toned El Salvador cup.
A high-toned Nicaragua cup showing a range of stone fruit, cocoa, and sweet nut in harmonious balance.
A fruit-forward natural processed Ethiopia cup with ballast from rich cocoa and floral suggestions throughout the profile.

Coffee Origin: San Cristobal, Cobán, Alta Verapaz, Guatemala

Coffee Origin: Cusco Department, La Convención Province, Santa Teresa District, Peru

Coffee Name: Ethiopia Sidama Naia Bomb Natural Vertical Reserve

A washed-process Ethiopia cup with leading notes of stone fruit and spicy florals and an especially inviting texture.
A balanced, sweetly nut-driven cup with pretty notes of baker’s chocolate and hints of oak forest that linger into the finish.
An exquisitely clean natural-processed Gesha cup from Ethiopia, elegantly structured and confidently aromatic.
A clean natural-processed Colombia cup from an unusual variety of Arabica — fruit-driven and chocolaty.
A classic washed Ethiopia cup: high-toned, rich and juicy, with notes of stone fruit and flowers throughout.

A sweet, pleasingly floral coffee animated by berry and cocoa notes throughout.
A big-bodied Kenya, zesty, deep, yet delicately layered in the aromatics.
An extremely rare, limited-production coffee procured by Miguel Meza of Paradise Roasters, unique in both backstory and cup.

A classic Kenya cup: sweet, tart, juicy all wrapped together with deep-toned red fruit and spicy floral notes.

Quiet, round, crisply balanced, with sweet stone fruit and cocoa supported by savory-leaning nut and oak.
An impressive example of Mexico-grown Geisha: elegant, delicate, nuanced, and deeply engaging.
An extremely rare, limited-production coffee procured by Miguel Meza of Paradise Roasters, well worth sampling for its balanced, pleasingly complex cup profile.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, south-central Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A sweet-toned natural Ethiopia cup that supplements ripe berry notes and dark chocolate with inviting hints of rich sandalwood.

A friendly, engaging PNG cup with leading notes of deep florals supported by sweet nut tones throughout the profile.

A floral- and spice-toned cup: balanced, complex, multilayered.

Coffee Origin: Hambela district, Oromia growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A pleasing Ethiopia natural: balanced, accessible, sweetly fruit-forward.

Coffee Origin: Ibicoara Municipality, Chapada Diamantina region, Bahia State, Brazil

Bottom Line: A pretty, richly fruit-toned natural-processed Kona cup, organic-certified.

Coffee Name: Café Granja La Esperanza Sudan Rume Natural

Bottom Line: A shape-shifter of a coffee: brilliant, original, absorbing.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing district, Big Island of Hawaii

Bottom Line: A citrus-driven, quite bright Guatemala cup with a pretty floral note akin to candied violet.

A deftly darker-roasted Yirgacheffe cup centered around notes of dark chocolate and spicy florals, with a particularly satisfying mouthfeel.
A fine Rwanda natural: clean, bright, juicy, mesmerizing.
A sweet-toned Rwanda cup with pretty floral and stone fruit notes throughout.
A floral- and tropical fruit-toned wet-processed Ethiopia cup.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia Region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A classic wet-processed Ethiopia cup: bright and vibrant, with leading notes of stone fruit and cocoa.

Bottom Line: A spice-driven, fruit-forward natural-processed Ethiopia cup: rich, resonant, clean, deep.

Bottom Line: A fine introduction to a rare variety of Arabica, Sudan Rume: crisp, bright, sweetly tart.

Coffee Origin: Piedra Candela, Chiriqui Province, far western Panama
Bottom Line: A dynamic coffee with complex aromatics that invoke the tropics—and a seemingly infinite finish, richly sweet and flavor-saturated.
A graceful, generously fruit- and floral-toned El Salvador cup with an exceptionally balanced structure and juicy acidity.

Coffee Name: Panama Elida Green Tip Gesha Natural
Bottom Line: An elegant, richly sweet natural-processed Panama Gesha with berry and chocolate notes throughout.
Superb version of the classic sweet-savory, crisply juicy, fragrantly floral-edged Kenya cup.
Superb Pacamara profile, crisply dry and spicy yet deeply, lavishly juicy sweet.

Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, “Big Island” of Hawaii
Bottom Line: Intense, bright but balanced cup with layered aromatic intrigue generated by a celebrated and rare tree variety.

The exciting Kenya tension between sweet and savory-tart is on display here, but a bit softer in expression perhaps, more tropical, than usual. A relaxed Kenya, authoritative yet delicate and approachable.
Low-toned and deeply rich, reminiscent of Ibarra Mexican chocolate with cinnamon, enveloped in fruit and nut tones.
Those who value a gently zesty sweetness should enjoy this delicate decaf cup. Easy on the palate, easy on the nervous system.
An engaging, confident Ethiopia cup with layered intrigue: flowers, fruit, aromatic wood.

Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, “Big Island” of Hawaii
Bottom Line: Coffee simply doesn’t get much better than this. Transcendently classic.

Coffee Name: Kenya Nyeri Othaya Gatugi Red Cherry Project AA
Bottom Line: A darker roast develops a savory-toned chocolate to complement a zesty citrus in this pleasingly contradictory Kenya.

Coffee Origin: San Martin Jilotepeque, Chimaltenango Department, Guatemala
Bottom Line: Delicate and graceful, yet authoritative in character; seductively sweet.
An unorthodox but original and engaging variation on the Kenya cup, juxtaposing sweetness and a musky, herby-savory edge.

Coffee Name: Static El Salvador Finca Maria Luisa
Coffee Origin: Santa Rosa, La Unión Department, El Salvador
Bottom Line: Those who value brisk, dry beverages should enjoy this coffee and its quiet, unorthodox aromatic intrigue.

Coffee Origin: Gichugu Division, Kirinyaga County, central Kenya
Bottom Line: Resonantly pungent Kenya, particularly attractive for its structure: sweet, tart and savory all at once, zesty yet seductive. Holds its character superbly as it cools.
Spicy-sweet, autumnal profile, complex and grown-up.
A lively, engaging spice-toned blend: crisp and richly sweet.
An engaging, richly sweet blend that will appeal to those who enjoy, for example, the crisp caramel tones of the crust on a creme brulee dessert.

Coffee Origin: Hambela District, Guji Zone, Oromia Region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A richly elegant cup that leads with deep fruit notes, as do many natural- processed coffees, though here the fruit is complicated by an engaging musk-like intrigue.

Coffee Origin: Aleta Wondo, Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A natural-processed Ethiopia coffee of intriguing depth, with a wide range of aroma/flavor notes, savory pipe tobacco to high-toned, spicy florals, to crisply sweet citrus marmalade.
The overall impression of this natural-processed Yirgacheffe cup is equal parts dried fruit and chocolate, nicely elaborated by spice suggestions (cinnamon, clove, nutmeg).
A gently spice-toned, floral- driven wet-processed Ethiopia cup with pleasing notes of cocoa throughout.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia Region, south-central Ethiopia
Bottom Line: Lavender-like flowers and hints of zesty pink peppercorn animate this crisply sweet wet-processed Ethiopia cup.

Coffee Origin: Gedeb District, Gedeo Zone, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A deeply and generously lush cup saved from sentimentality by a crisp, incense-like, slightly savory edge. Very wide range of aromatics.

Coffee Origin: Odo Shakiso District, Guji Zone, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A lively and crisply sweet, fruit-forward natural-processed Ethiopia cup.
A deeply sweet natural-processed Ethiopia cup, with stone fruit and brandy notes as parallel throughlines.

Coffee Origin: Hambela Wamena District, Guji Zone, Oromia Region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A delicate, richly sweet wet-processed Ethiopia: spice, herb, fruit and flowers in intricate balance.

Coffee Origin: Hambela District, Guji Zone, Oromia Region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: An inviting wet-processed Ethiopia cup. Invokes a walk through a citrus orchard in spring, with a bonus of sweet herb and cocoa tones.
Mysterious and extraordinary in the Kenya style: simultaneously sweet, savory, tart and entirely and grandly vibrant.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: This very light-roasted decaffeinated coffee may suggest a fine, complex Chinese black tea in some respects, though it ultimately enforces its coffee identity with its tart structure and light-footed authority. Oddly idiosyncratic in its aromatics, but quite free of the disturbing wood notes characteristic of many decaffeinated coffees.
An engaging, classic Kenya cup, with sweet and savory notes in balance, including an intriguing undertone suggesting the flavor of Russian rye bread.
A straight-ahead Panama cup: crisp, citrus- and chocolate-toned with inviting tropical fruit notes.
A deeply intense, focused Kenya coffee with an especially appealing mouthfeel, velvety and lively.
A compelling Gesha coffee from Guatemala, at turns sweet, savory, tart and spice-toned, all in harmonious balance.

Coffee Origin: El Salto, Boquete growing region, Panama
Bottom Line: An unusual variation on the dry or natural process applied to a fine Panama coffee, netting a cup rich with chocolate and fruit notes: elegant, high-toned, with pleasing notes of sweet ferment.
Hits all the classic Kenya notes: pungent with deep fruit and florals, supported by a simultaneously bright yet savory structure.
A richly sweet, spice-toned washed Ethiopia cup, with a throughline of intriguing bergamot and fennel-like notes.
An understated Yirgacheffe cup, quiet in aroma, with a balanced sweet-savory through-line carried by apricot and spicy aromatic wood notes.
A thrilling ride of a Kenya: balanced, deep, rich, and intriguingly spice-toned.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Cumbres del Poas “Perla Negra”
Coffee Origin: Sabanilla de Alajuela growing region, Costa Rica
Bottom Line: An engaging natural-processed Costa Rica driven by spicy floral notes and suggestions of dried stone fruit. Organically grown.

Coffee Name: Gold Mountain Coffee Growers Daniel’s Caturra Microlot
Bottom Line: Original in aromatics and deep in structure. Savory-leaning with rich sweetness and a spice throughline.
More elegant than the term “funky” implies; nonetheless will most appeal to those who enjoy coffees that are decidedly driven by the richness of deep fruit notes.

Coffee Name: Tolliver’s Reserve Nicaragua Gold Mountain Fruit Candy Nanolot
Bottom Line: As the coffee’s name implies, the cup is characterized by notes suggesting tangy hard candy (watermelon, green apple), complicated by sweet-toned spices and aromatic wood.

A solid, complexly structured coffee from a roaster that has supported the coffee producers of Nicaragua for decades, through thick and thin. The Smithsonian Bird-Friendly certification is a rare and impeccable environmental credential.

Coffee Name: Nicaragua Un Regalo de Dios Bourbon
Bottom Line: A confident floral and sweetly spice-toned Nicaragua from trees of the heirloom Bourbon variety: elegant, deeply rich, sweetly and roundly resonant.
An engaging ride of a Nicaragua Gesha: high-toned, balanced, discreetly confident, complete.

Coffee Origin: Gedeb District, Gedeo Zone, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: An elegant, sensuous experience of a dried-in-the-fruit or natural-processed Ethiopia coffee. Harmoniously sweet, tart and savory with a stunning range of aromatic intrigue.

Coffee Origin: Gedeb District, Gedeo Zone, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: An unusual washed Ethiopia cup, suggesting a very adult version of a chocolate and root beer float perhaps, but with deep floral and fruit complications.
A flavor-saturated Kenya cup characterized by sweet fruit and floral tones at the top, fine musk and chocolate underneath.
An inviting Guatemala, notable for its savory, tart-leaning sweetness, high-toned and layered.
Offers the depth and balance of a fine Pacamara, simultaneously sweet, savory and tart, with a quietly resonant set of aroma and flavor notes.
A washed Ethiopia cup with a lot going on: high-toned fruit, crisply sweet citrus zest, and a confident ballast of herb-laced butterscotch.
A surprising Colombia cup, unconventional in regard to processing method (dried-in-the-fruit full natural), which contributes to a fruit-forward, yet cohesively balanced, profile.
A thrill of a natural-processed Ethiopia: fruit, florals and savory notes in intricate, lively harmony.
A simultaneously savory-leaning yet floral- and sweet-toned honey-processed coffee.

Coffee Name: Static Don Eli La Pastora Tarrazu Costa Rica
Bottom Line: A honey-processed Costa Rica cup, enticing for its high-toned, vivacious herb notes enveloped in suggestions of rich florals and sweet nuts.
A big-bodied Colombia that leads unapologetically and impressively with sweet-toned spice notes.
An inviting honey-processed Ethiopia, with cocoa, fruit and floral notes both rounded and turned gently crisp by a tactful medium-dark roast.
An interesting choice for those who prefer to find the sweetness in their cup expressed in floral and aromatic wood notes rather than in the more typical fruit.
A roast at the edge between medium and medium-dark promotes pleasant smoke notes in this Guatemala, while still allowing spice, fruit and floral notes to exert their presence and authority.
An aromatic-wood-framed Brazil peaberry with pretty floral undertones.
The bittersweet structure, dried fruit notes and vanilla-toned flowers pleasantly nudge this coffee toward a darker roast profile, even though this is a medium-roasted bean.
A light-footed and crisply elegant Kenya; if the big, emphatic Kenyas are Cabernets, this one is a Pinot Noir.

Although Uganda has struggled over the years to produce top Arabica coffees worthy of its excellent terroirs and hard-working growers, producers have clearly succeeded here with this very impressive, quite distinctive offering in the deep, resonant style of the best Central Africa coffees.

Coffee Origin: Marcala growing region, La Paz Department, Honduras
Bottom Line: Unusual Central America profile, tart but starchy, candyish yet savory. Those who value the sweet/savory coffees of Central Africa origins like Rwanda or Burundi may particularly enjoy this attractive but atypical Honduras.
A light-footed, vivacious wet-processed Ethiopia cup. Might make a refreshing cold or iced coffee.
A nuanced, complex Colombia cup that leads with lush floral notes and stone fruit grounded by suggestions of rich cocoa.

Coffee Origin: Baringo and Nakura Counties, central Kenya
Bottom Line: An elegant and complete Kenya; pungent, delicate yet deep. Think fine red table wines.

Coffee Origin: Baringo and Nakura Counties, central Kenya
Bottom Line: Classic Kenya cup: honey, citrus and spice.
A light roast develops the delicacy and gentle vivacity of this cleanly understated yet spectacularly aromatic dried-in-the-fruit or “natural” Gesha profile.
A high-toned flowers-and-cocoa version of the Gesha profile, classic, intense and exhilarating.
Crisp yet lush, deep, intricate, a classic Gesha from Hacienda Esmeralda, the ground zero of the Gesha variety’s take-off to fame.
Intensely sweet, intensely roasty, intensely Gesha. And given it’s Gesha, an impressive value.
The Gesha character exerts a quiet but decisive influence in this classic, sweetly bright and balanced Guatemala.
Hints of Gesha complexity contribute resonant intrigue to this classic, gently pungent Guatemala.

Coffee Name: Carmen Geisha El Palomar Best of Panama #4 Carlos Aguilera
Bottom Line: Extraordinary shifting and intricate flavor and aroma supported by a flawless structure, classic in its sweet-tart balance.

Coffee Origin: Mantiqeiras de Minas growing region, Brazil, Brazil
Bottom Line: An accessible, deeply sweet, caramel-toned Brazil cup. Those who avoid aggressive acidity but enjoy a lighter-roasted, very gently bright cup should particularly value this selection.
A rich, complex, rather atypical Colombia coffee that deepens as you linger with the cup: bright but resonant, deeply spice-toned.
A high-toned, elegantly crisp, washed Yirgacheffe cup with a cocoa throughline.
A very distinctive and original Guatemala, fusing sweet/savory depth with delicate, lively nut and floral aromatics.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica La Cereza Roja Semi-Washed
Bottom Line: A discreetly fruit-toned, honey-processed coffee with aromatic wood notes as ballast.
A sweet-toned, zesty washed Yirgacheffe coffee that leads with rich floral notes grounded by suggestions of grapefruit zest.
A deeply rich, layered Kenya cup with savory sweetness characteristic of this celebrated origin’s most classic coffees.

The slightly darker roast is felt rather than tasted in this extraordinarily deeply stated, complete version of the great Gesha profile. Those who may enjoy the aromatic extravagance of the Gesha profile but put off by Gesha’s often brightly assertive acidity should particularly value this rounder, yet still exhilaratingly vibrant version.
Quiet, elegant Peru, with chocolate and ripe fruit notes rounded and deepened by a very tactful, backgrounded medium-dark roast.
A no-apologies dark roast that retains resonant complexity and vibrant balance throughout the profile.

A rich, idiosyncratic version of an already idiosyncratic coffee type, a darker roasted wet-hulled Sumatra. We didn’t register much of the famous Sumatra earth or pipe tobacco, but we did get a big, spicy yet fudgy chocolate and a complex pungent sweetness.
A quiet, accessible darker-roasted coffee, sweet and caramelly with a brisk, zesty edge.

Coffee Name: Mocha Java Blend Fair Trade Organic
Bottom Line: A twisty version of the ancient Mocha-Java blend, probably quite authentic with its suggestions of wood, spicy nut and chocolate.

Coffee Origin: Yirgacheffe growing region, Gedeo Zone, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A pungent, intricate darker-roasted Ethiopia Yirgacheffe, lushly floral in front with an engagingly bittersweet, savory-edged depth.
Unusual juxtaposition of aromatic wood, flowers and cocoa animate a zesty, bittersweet medium-dark-roasted blend.

Coffee Origin: Yirgacheffe growing region, Gedeo Zone, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A delicate, floral-and-cocoa wet-processed Ethiopia turned richly crisp by a tactful darker roast.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia
Bottom Line: An authentic “forest floor” style of Sumatra coffee brought to a briskly decisive darker roast, enriching without obscuring its pleasing earthy idiosyncrasy.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia Province, Indonesia, Indonesia
Bottom Line: A classic wet-hulled Sumatra, equal parts floral- and earth-toned, with rich aromatic wood and chocolate notes throughout.
An enticing, classic Kenya: bright, juicy, crisp, powerful yet finely balanced.

Coffee Origin: Shakiso growing district, Guji Zone, Oromia Region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: This natural-processed Ethiopia cup is an engaging study in contrasts: sweetly fermenty fruit notes juxtaposed with suggestions of gently scorched aromatic wood.
A crisp, spice-framed Congo natural with suggestions of rich almond notes throughout the profile.
An attractive washed Yirgacheffe, peachy sweet and spicy-savory.
A medium-dark roast nicely develops this wet-processed Ethiopia’s chocolate and spice notes. A good choice for those who enjoy strongly stated profiles.

Coffee Name: Ninety Plus Gesha Estates Limited Batch #227
Bottom Line: An extraordinarily original coffee, both in story (Gesha variety, unorthodox processing) and in its stunning aromatics, both intricately complex, yet grandly and resonantly complete.
A crisply high-toned washed Ethiopia coffee offering a fine balance of sweet fruit and aromatic wood notes.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia Province, Indonesia, Indonesia
Bottom Line: An enigmatic, deep Sumatra cup, with classic layering of lush fruit and foresty notes of tobacco, orchid and fresh earth.
A resonantly engaging Kenya cup: smoothly bright acidity, sweet fruit and floral notes and a deep, savory throughline.

Coffee Name: Calle San Juan Costa Rica Honey
Coffee Origin: Sabanilla de Alajuela growing region, Costa Rica
Bottom Line: A balanced, sweet-toned Costa Rica cup with a spicy floral notes thorughout.

Coffee Origin: Odo Shakiso District, Guji Zone, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A sweet-toned natural Ethiopia cup with elegantly engaging floral and dried fruit notes.
A deeply engaging floral-toned Colombia cup with suggestions of chocolate and succulent stone fruit throughout, as well as hints of savory spice.
A tactful darker-roasted coffee with deep chocolate notes throughout, complicated by raisin and sweet floral hints.
A particularly deep-toned version of Kenya’s characteristic style of sweet-tart fruit and lively, bright acidity.
Another compelling Aida Batlle coffee from her El Salvador farm, with deep fruit and cocoa tones and spicy floral notes throughout.

Coffee Origin: Murang’a Foothills, Aberdare Ridge, Central Province, Kenya
Bottom Line: Complex, intensely pungent, deeply sweet-savory. Concord grape, honey, marjoram, narcissus, blood orange zest in aroma and cup. Juicy, engaging acidity; plush, syrupy mouthfeel. The resonant, long, flavor-laden finish sustains all of the notes from the cup plus a cinnamon-like hint of spice.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Finca Kilimanjaro Cascara Fermentation Aida Batlle
Bottom Line: The originality of this sweetly intricate, multilayered cup is doubtless owing both to a distinguished tree variety – Kenya’s famous SL28 – as well as to an innovative processing wrinkle involving conducting the fermentation step in an infusion of cascara, or the dried husk of the coffee fruit.
A sweet, floral-toned Rwanda cup with ballast from tart citrus and savory aromatic wood notes.
An accessible, sweet-toned Rwanda coffee saturated with spicy floral complication.

Coffee Name: El Salvador La Loma Gloria Washed
Bottom Line: An accessible, balanced, crisply sweet cup offering quiet aromatic surprises.

Coffee Origin: Ka’u growing region, Big Island of Hawaii
Bottom Line: A dried-in-the-fruit or natural cup that engages by way of sweet florals and appealing tart fruit notes.
Blueberry central! A fruit-toned natural cup that paradoxically conjures sherry-like wine enveloped in dark chocolate.
A complex Rwanda cup that rewards patience with an unfolding of sweet fruit and floral notes juxtaposed with suggestions of savory herbs.
Poised between rich sweetness and bold savory tones, this Kenya is refined and deeply satisfying.
A Rwanda tactfully roasted to the dark edge of medium; chocolate-centered with floral and spice notes complicated by a hint of smoky aromatic wood.

Coffee Name: Montaña de Abi Anny Ruth El Salvador
Bottom Line: An inviting dried-in-the-fruit or “natural” coffee from El Salvador, crisply spice-toned and fruit-forward.

An intriguing Congo cup from a cooperative that is leading the recovery of the Kivu region from civil war, and a sensory gift for those who enjoy savory-leaning coffees complicated and deepened by berry and citrus notes.

Coffee Origin: Puna District, Big Island of Hawaii
Bottom Line: A natural-processed coffee that exhibits grace and finesse in its fruit-forward elegance.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Anny Ruth Red Honey
Bottom Line: A classic and inviting Central America cup: crisp, sweet, balanced, plush.
An accessible, high-toned coffee with inviting pear, vanilla-like florals and aromatic wood notes.

Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, “Big Island” of Hawaii
Bottom Line: Unusual, pleasing and wide-ranging in aroma and flavor, from chocolate to citrus blossom and savory spice to hints of tropical fruit.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia Province, Indonesia, Indonesia
Bottom Line: A flavor-saturated Sumatra with lively citrus, elegant fruit and lush tobacco notes.
An appealing Kenya cup, driven by berry and spice notes and vanilla-like florals.
Satisfying chocolate and nut notes nearly carry the day in this briskly bittersweet coffee from Puerto Rico.

Coffee Name: Gesha Village Estate Bench Maji Gesha G1
Bottom Line: An elegant washed Gesha from Ethiopia: juicy, delicately intense, flower-driven.
A deep, sweet-savory Colombia cup with inviting chocolate and tart-fruit notes.
This very sensitively light-roasted coffee offers a delicate, refreshing take on spirits barrel-conditioned coffee.
This complex expression of delicate but powerfully aromatic green coffee, a hint of wine-toned alcohol and distinct roast notes should please those who like a roasty but nuanced and original cup.
A resonant, complexly layered, quite original cup.

Coffee Origin: Apaneca-Ilamatapec growing region, western El Salvador
Bottom Line: Balanced, quietly zesty; the wine gently but explicitly complicates acidity and flavor in this graceful El Salvador.

Coffee Origin: Puna District, Big Island of Hawaii
Bottom Line: A beverage of contrasts. Lush but crisp in its floral- and cocoa-toned aromatics; sweet but bracingly bitterish and dry in structure. The aromatics prevail in a smooth, refreshing finish.

Coffee Origin: Dolok Sanggul, Lintong growing region, North Indonesia, Indonesia
Bottom Line: The great wet-hulled Sumatra profile takes on a particularly graceful resonance in this traditionally aged version.
A sweetly herbaceous, crisp, cocoa-toned Colombia cup.
An accessible, sweetly nut- and spice-toned Brazil cup.

Coffee Name: Ninety Plus Estate Panama Gesha Lycello
Bottom Line: A big-bodied, high-toned, crisply sweet Panama Gesha that resonates with citrus and cocoa notes throughout.
Attractive darker-roasted Costa Rica, pungent and chocolaty with a zesty orange edge.

Coffee Name: Peru Rayos del Sol Single Farm
Bottom Line: A straightforward cup with an appealing throughline of sweet nut and fruit tones and gentle acidity.
A crisply sweet, ripe-berry-driven Yirgacheffe cup with attractive chocolate tones throughout.
A commanding Kenya coffee: sophisticated yet playful, with tropical fruit and sweet floral tones in harmonious balance.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: An essentially sweet natural Sidamo cup with savory depth and a crisp, spice-toned throughline.
For those who enjoy the virtues of decidedly light-roasted coffees, this Peru offers a delicately floral cup with high-toned cacao notes throughout.
A lovely breakfast-style blend with gentle ripe-fruit tones (the honey-processed coffees in the blend?) animated by a sweetly tart vivacity.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Sonoran Estate Red Catuai
Bottom Line: A delightfully balanced Costa Rica cup, classic in its expression of crisp, gentle acidity and ripe fruit and sweet floral notes.

Coffee Origin: Matas de Minas growing region, Brazil, Brazil
Bottom Line: A pleasing, accessible cup for those who enjoy mild, sweetly nut- and chocolate-toned Brazils.
A deeply inviting natural Gesha cup, splendidly structured and fulfilling in its range of clean fruit and floral tones sustained from aroma to finish.
An enticingly unusual coffee in general, but a classic in the Burundi sense: crisp, simultaneously sweet and savory-tart, as well as high-toned.
A very cleanly expressed dried-in-the-fruit Yirgacheffe cup, richly spice-toned with deeply sweet floral notes.
A fine but affordable blend characterized by both its sweet delicacy and rich depth.
A crisply sweet-savory cup, with a throughline of rich chocolate and sweetly tart fruit notes.
An accessible, sweet Rwanda cup with appealing berry and bittersweet citrus notes in aroma and flavor.
A gently bright, exuberant washed Ethiopia cup: classically sweet, richly tart, intricately aromatic.
An intricately composed, delicate, crisply sweet Ethiopia with zesty citrus tones throughout.
An intense, confident Kenya cup that will appeal to those who like savory-leaning yet sweet-toned coffees.
A graceful, pretty washed Ethiopia cup with deep floral notes up front, grounded by cocoa and citrus tones.
Pushes the envelope on classic Kenya sweet-savory balance, leaning more toward the savory, though its tart, spicy core is saturated throughout by floral and cocoa notes.
A lovely medium-dark roasted coffee showing deep fruit- and floral-toned sweetness from aroma to finish.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia Province, Indonesia, Indonesia
Bottom Line: A rich, spicy-sweet Sumatra with cocoa tones and suggestions of vanilla-like flowers throughout.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: An unusually clean and poised natural-processed Ethiopia cup, sweetly crisp and buoyant.
A classic Kenya cup: sweetly tart, delicately herbaceous, flavor-saturated from aroma to finish.

Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, “Big Island” of Hawaii
Bottom Line: An exciting and rare coffee with an extraordinarily bright acidity and broad aromatic scope.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia Region, Sidama Province, Ethiopia
Bottom Line: An appealing natural-processed Ethiopia cup with a crisp but lush, edge-of-fermenty fruit.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia Province, Indonesia, Indonesia
Bottom Line: Will appeal to those who value the classic Sumatra wet-hulled profile, with sweet fruit and spicy floral notes complicating a throughline of rich pipe tobacco.
A fruit-forward Panama cup with a crisp, lively throughline of fragrant aromatic wood.
A distinct strawberry note, somewhere between strawberry jam and strawberry guava, sweetly contrasting with a slightly pungent, oaky crispness, give this coffee its unusual character.

Coffee Name: Yemen Port of Mokha Hayma Microlot
Bottom Line: An exquisitely composed Yemen coffee, almost other-worldly in its array of fruit and floral notes, all enveloped in a crisp chocolate.

Coffee Origin: San Adolfo, Acevedo, Huila Department, Colombia
Bottom Line: A Colombia coffee with an exhilarating range of sensation: both delicate and juicy, floral and spice-toned.

Coffee Name: Colombia Gustavo de Jesus Rivera Microlot
Bottom Line: A confident, juicy-sweet Colombia coffee, satisfyingly complete in structure and lively in aromatics.

Coffee Origin: Limu Woreda, Oromia Zone, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A decidedly fruit-centered natural-processed Ethiopia, with a tasteful edge of sweet ferment.
An attractive Kenya cup for those who enjoy a bold, tart-leaning acidity, with a bright sweetness emerging beneath its initial assertion.
A lush, aromatically bold Kenya cup: floral-toned with deep fruit notes and rich savory resonance.
Classically Kenya: sweet, tart and deeply savory all at once, resonating around floral-toned herb and pungent berry notes.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia Region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A cocoa-and fruit-toned natural-processed Ethiopia with a pleasantly brandy-toned hint of sweet ferment.
Should please lovers of the classic Kenya style: big, juicy and sweet-savory in structure, pungently berry- and lavender-toned in aromatics.
An accessible washed Ethiopia cup, sweetly balanced and gently animated by floral and spice notes.
A compelling and quietly original blend, unusual in that it contains coffees from four origins roasted to different levels and combined, much like a cuvee in the wine industry.

Coffee Name: Papua New Guinea PB Kimel Estate
Coffee Origin: Waghi Valley, Western Highlands Province, Papua New Guinea
Bottom Line: A particularly elegant Papua New Guinea peaberry coffee: juicy-sweet and crisply tart, finely balanced from aroma to finish.

Coffee Name: Panama La Esmeralda Noria Enero Geisha
Bottom Line: A complex expression of Gesha’s potential beauty, with lush florals, sweet and tart fruit notes, and crisp cocoa throughout.
One of the most impressive Rwanda coffees to have reached our cupping table in years: crisp, deeply sweet and balanced, with a resonant savory/umami throughline.
An exquisite experience of Sumatra coffee: exotic, deeply sweet, umami-rich.
An elegant natural-processed rendition of the classic Gesha cup, with notes of floral-toned musk and cocoa revealed in complex layers.
A bold, sweetly spice-toned natural-processed Gesha from Ethiopia, the origin of this famous and still rare coffee variety.

Coffee Origin: Sidikalang, Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia
Bottom Line: A big, resonant, sweetly earth-toned and floral Sumatra coffee.
An impressive citrus and sweet spice-toned Yirgacheffe cup, impressively certified: both organic and Fair Trade.

Coffee Origin: Hambela Wamena District, Guji Zone, Oromia region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: An inviting and accessible natural-processed Ethiopia: crisp, sweet-tart and delicate.

Coffee Origin: Hambela Wamena District, Guji Zone, Oromia Region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: An intricately layered, elegantly rich natural-processed Ethiopia cup.

Coffee Origin: Piedra Candela, Chiriqui Province, far western Panama
Bottom Line: A lovely natural-processed Gesha from a highly regarded farm: elegant, lively, flavor-laden.

An unusually gentle yet fully expressed variation on the Kenya theme of lush, berryish sweetness fused with the crisply savory. Its grace, sweetness, and soft but lively acidity makes it one of the more accessible Kenyas we have cupped for some time.
An unconventional, rather original cup, woody yet sweet, with engaging crisp nut and baker’s chocolate notes.
An extraordinary coffee with very limited availability: exotically aromatic, balanced, uniquely composed.
An exciting natural Yirgacheffe cup, both classic in brightly sweet structure and exotic in lush, complex detail.
A Pacamara on steroids, in the best possible sense, with butterscotch and lavender, in particular, in 3-D.
A costly but rare and prestigious gift for the coffee-lover who values intricate yet elegant natural-processed Geshas.
One of the loveliest blends we tested in 2016, distinguished by rich aromatics and appealing tropical flavor notes.
A very pretty citrus-toned Gesha, packaged for the holidays in a reusable glass jar. Organic to boot.

Coffee Origin: Limu Woreda, Oromia Zone, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A lovely, balanced natural-processed Ethiopia from Limu, a growing area less-known than the iconic Yirgacheffe and Sidamo regions.
An unusual Gesha, more nut-toned than floral, hearty rather than delicate, likely to particularly appeal to those who prefer a slightly darker-roasted presentation of this celebrated coffee variety.
A classic coffee blend, sweet and rich, packaged in a hand-printed bag featuring local art, and one in a series of Red Rooster’s special Advent calendar coffee releases.

Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, “Big Island” of Hawaii
Bottom Line: A classic revival of the original Kona strain of Typica: sweet-tart fruit notes and rich chocolate and florals. Limited availability.
A compelling holiday blend, named for the popular winter-season flower: sweet, spicy, richly floral.

Coffee Name: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Natural Celinga Foge Grade 1
Coffee Origin: Guanga District, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A big, resonant dried-in-the-fruit Yirgacheffe, brightly fruit-toned and lushly floral.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Las Lajas Alma Negra
Coffee Origin: Sabanilla de Alajuela, Central Valley, Costa Rica
Bottom Line: A discreet ferment turns the fruit toward cider in this crisp natural-process Costa Rica.
An impressive dark roast, round, balanced and chocolate- and plum-toned.
A soft, quiet-spoken darker roast, gently chocolaty and raisin-toned.
A solid blend with holiday appeal: nut-toned chocolate and vanilla-like florals.
A good choice for those who appreciate a tactfully dark-roasted blend that maintains its fruit and chocolate notes throughout the profile, with support from deep spice tones.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Las Lajas Red Honey
Coffee Origin: Sabanilla de Alajuela growing region, Costa Rica
Bottom Line: A sweetly crisp, accessible honey-processed Costa Rica cup.
A fine holiday blend for those who favor darker-roasted coffees with gentle acidity and rich chocolate notes.
Reminiscent in part of a very sophisticated essence of root beer float, this attractive Kenya is deep, sweet and richly smooth.

Coffee Origin: Toraja growing region, south-central Sulawesi, Indonesia
Bottom Line: An invitingly juicy, yet intriguingly sweet-savory Sulawesi coffee.
