Bottom Line: Anyone who can afford this extraordinary coffee: elegant yet intense; resonant, intricate. The whisky suggestion, very clear and pleasing yet exhilaratingly clean, is particularly impressive.

Coffee Name: Harfusa Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Fair Trade Organic
Bottom Line: Those who value both classic structure and the seething aromatic surprise of a great wet-processed Ethiopia.
Those who value an elegantly bright, honey-toned, light-roasted Colombia.

Coffee Name: Guatemala Plan del Guayabo Estate SL28 Winey
Bottom Line: Those who value a fruit-driven, natural-processed Guatemala with deep, musky floral tones.

Coffee Name: Kenya Nyeri Kiama FCS Ichuga Factory Peaberry
Bottom Line: Anyone who values the paradox of delicacy and power in a classically beautiful Kenya cup.
Those who value a classic Kenya balanced richly and gracefully between fruit and chocolate.
Those who enjoy a crisp, vibrant coffee, original in its aromatics.
Those who value a richly composed, lyrically expressive, classic Gesha cup.
Those interested in a uniquely and seductively floral experience of coffee via the great Gesha variety.
Those interested in a thoughtfully curated blend of outstanding Ethiopia and Kenya coffees in an impressively balanced, fruit- and floral-toned cup.
Those who value an envelopingly sweet and spicy, resonantly deep cup.
Those who value the intense, complexly nut-toned fruit of a more savory style of natural or dried-in-the-fruit Gesha.
Those looking for a balanced, engaging and complexly layered blend with a persuasively holiday-themed set of flavor notes.

Coffee Origin: Piedra Candela, Chiriqui Province, western Panama
Bottom Line: Poised and lyrically complete version of the great Gesha profile: lush yet pure.

Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, “Big Island” of Hawaii
Bottom Line: Anyone interested in a particularly distinguished and distinctive floral-toned experience of the Kona cup.
Those who appreciate a vigorously hearty, spice- and floral-toned cup.
An appealingly dynamic, sweetly spicy holiday blend at an excellent price.
Those looking for great value in a nicely rounded, delicately spicy holiday cup.

Coffee Origin: Santa Ana growing region, El Salvador
Bottom Line: Anyone who values a richly floral- and spice-toned variation on the great SL-28 cup.
Those who enjoy a classic, dark-fruit-driven, floral Kenya.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Sidama Province, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: Those who love big, fruit-forward natural Ethiopia coffees with seductive spice notes.

Coffee Origin: Chiriqui, Boquete growing region, western Panama
Bottom Line: Those interested in experiencing a lush, exciting non-Gesha coffee from a highly regarded producer of the rare and expensive Gesha variety.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica El Jordan Natural Small-Lot Reserve
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy musky, fruit- and floral-toned dried-in-the-fruit Central America coffees.
Those who enjoy a sweet, musky Guatemala with engaging floral complication.
Those who value a delicate but lively cup, citrusy brisk, peachy sweet.

Coffee Name: Panama La Esmeralda Bosque Lot 1 Gesha
Bottom Line: Those who value a complex, multi-layered expression of the great Gesha profile.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Santa Lucia Cup of Excellence #7
Bottom Line: Those who value a cup with graceful balance between bright, juicy citrus and crisp nut.

Coffee Name: Finca La Mula Panama Geisha Natural
Bottom Line: Those who seek a dynamic, expansively structured cup with graceful balance between fruit and floral notes.
Those who like a big, full-bodied coffee with exotic-spice aroma and flavor.

Coffee Origin: Hambela District, Oromia growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: Those who value a big, flamboyant, floral-and-fruit-saturated natural Ethiopia.
Those who value a fine Kenya in the big, bright, spicy floral style.
Those who are intrigued by a delicately intense floral and nutty cup with fine structure and intricate aromatics.

Coffee Origin: Hambela District, Oromia growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: Those who value a clean, zesty, intricately engaging rendition of the southern Ethiopia cup, dry-boned but juicy sweet.
Those who value the more austere, tartly spicy style of the great Kenya profile.
Those who appreciate a lighter roasted, delicately pungent Yirgacheffe.
Superb coffee in every respect: classic yet exotic.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Alberto Guardia Venecia Honey

Bottom Line: A sensitive roast on the dark end of medium develops an attractive, chocolaty depth in this classic Guatemala.
Those who like tree-fruit flavors paired with light floral and herbal notes in a crisp cup.

Coffee Origin: Valle del Cauca growing region, Colombia
Bottom Line: Those who value a big, ringing version of a classic Colombia cup: vibrant, simple yet grandly complete. And certified organic.
Bittersweet in the very best sense: simultaneously honey sweet and crisply savory, with engaging and intricate aromatic nuance. And organically grown.

Coffee Name: Nicaragua Cafe Vidita Los Congos Pacamara Natural
Bottom Line: Superb dried-in-the-fruit Pacamara: deep, resonant, complexly layered, original.
Those who enjoy a slight edge of whiskyish fruit ferment animating a complex, balanced, floral-toned cup.
Those aficionados interested in an extremely unusual coffee: The huge-beaned Maragogipe variety is rare enough; the peaberry grade of a Maragogipe is rarer still.

Coffee Origin: Yauco growing region, central Puerto Rico
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a crisp, lively cup with considerable dry chocolate and sweet floral intrigue.
Aficionados of the classic Kenya cup: big, bright, dry but juicy, deeply nuanced with flowers and sweetly tart fruit.
A quietly striking, original version of the great Gesha profile.
An appealingly deep, sweet-savory, pungently wintery profile.
Those who enjoy a graceful and complexly sweet cup. The acidity in particular is gentle, yet lyric and lively.
Those who value gently bright coffees, delicate, aromatic, pure.
A roast at the darkish end of medium develops the sweet-savory, deep floral complexity of this fine Yirgacheffe.
Those who enjoy the subtle, complexly sweet ferment and lush flowers of the more rustic style of dried-in-the-fruit or “natural” coffees.

Coffee Origin: Gedeb District, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A rather light roast develops the delicate, zesty vivacity of this fine wet-processed Ethiopia.
The quietly adventurous. Subtly original in aroma and flavor: crisply and sweetly pungent, incense-like.
Those who value a brisk, quietly zesty cup with subtle aromatic intrigue.
Chocolate lovers. A tart, but sweetly nuanced, chocolate note dominates in this attractive Guatemala.
Certified Fair Trade coffee buyers with a taste for quiet adventure. The note we are calling brie cheese is not unpleasant, and resonates with the savory-sweet structure and rose-and-cocoa aromatics.
A roast on the darkish end of medium turns the fruit and chocolate crisp and deep.
Those who seek a beautifully structured coffee that delivers a lyrically complex aroma, rich, seductive flavor and crisp, authoritative finish.
Those who enjoy a complexly fruit and floral-toned yet cleanly balanced rendition of the great Ethiopia dried-in-the-fruit profile.
Complex, original and subtly layered organic holiday blend.

Coffee Name: Bean Brain Reserve Perla Negra Costa Rica
Coffee Origin: Alajuela growing region, Central Valley, Costa Rica
Bottom Line: A fine dried-in-the-fruit coffee at the intriguing intersection of cherryish fruit, chocolate, whisky and deep, lily-like flowers.

Coffee Origin: Wellega, Sidama and Yirgacheffe growing regions, southern and western Ethiopia
Bottom Line: The intricate, fragrant overlapping of sweet floral and savory herb tendencies may particularly appeal to those who enjoy complex aperitifs and digestifs.
Those who value an elegantly subtle version of the fruit-and-floral-toned exuberance typical of fine dried-in-the-fruit or “natural”-processed Ethiopian coffees.
Classicists. A superb Colombia, sweet yet brisk, balanced in structure and complete in nuance.
Nice Kenya for those who avoid the often bright Kenya acidity but value the pungent, savory-sweet berry and dark chocolate tendencies of the type.
Those who value subtlety and resonance in a gently roast-rounded, sweetly bright and floral wet-processed Ethiopia.
A classic dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia with the usual lush fruit rounded to a crisp, floral-toned chocolate by a tactful darkish roast.
Those who lean toward the sweet and juicy side of the classic intricacy and elegance of the great Kenya profile.

Coffee Origin: Hambela District, Oromia growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a classic dried-in-the-fruit, “natural” profile, fruit-and-brandy-saturated but clean finishing.

Coffee Origin: Santa Ana growing region, El Salvador
Bottom Line: Those who value richly spicy, fragrantly wood-toned beverages (certain digestifs and aperitifs, for example).
Aficionados curious about the rare, huge-beaned Maragogipe variety of Arabica. This version displays unusually full mouthfeel and a sweet, spice-and-flowers wood character.
Aficionados interested in sampling this now rare, once flourishing coffee origin, and anyone who values a delicately crisp, strawberry-and-nut-toned cup.

Coffee Origin: Palencia, Fraijanes Plateau growing region, central Guatemala
Bottom Line: Those who value a delicate but zesty cup, light-footed and lively.
Those who value a fine, classic juxtaposition of a plummy, plump juiciness and crisp nut and cedar.

Coffee Name: Guatemala El Injerto Pandora del Carmen Auction-Lot

Bottom Line: A very slight, felicitous hint of ferment complicates the fundamental, natural sweetness of this fine traditionally styled Guatemala.

Coffee Name: Honduras Santa Barbara Finca Las Brisas
Bottom Line: Those who value the complete, balanced structure and quietly engaging aromatics of a classic Central American cup.
Those who value a coffee both delicate and lush, pure yet musky and deep.

Coffee Origin: Blue Mountain growing region, eastern Jamaica.
Bottom Line: Those who value the sweetness, full mouthfeel and sweet cocoa notes that made this celebrated origin famous.
Those who value a big but balanced version of the lushly sweet, fruit-forward style of “natural” or dried-in-the-fruit coffee.
Those who value depth and resonance in a complexly pungent Central Africa coffee.

Coffee Origin: Hambela district, Oromia growing region, southern Ethiopia
Bottom Line: A fine version of the older-fashioned style of dried-in-the-fruit or “natural” Ethiopia coffee: Chocolate, cherry and brandy; a grown-up dessert in a cup.
Superb Kenya, extraordinarily bright and juicy but without a trace of sharpness. Aroma and flavor are deeply expressed and engaging.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who prefer a rounder, deeper version of the typical floral-and-cocoa-toned Ethiopia wet-processed cup, and one that is reassuringly certified.

Coffee Origin: Cañas Verdes, Boquete growing region, western Panama.
Bottom Line: Those who value exhilarating aroma and flavor supported by a complexly expressed structure as crisply dry as it is juicily sweet.
Those who value a quietly comprehensive cup, with crisp nut and cacao notes and a softening bloom of sweet flowers.

Coffee Origin: Santa Maria de Dota valley, Tarrazu growing region, Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Those who value a crisp, refreshing cup, sweet yet gently drying, with quietly intriguing aromatics.
A splendid Kenya, classically complete in structure and leaning toward the sweet and floral in its gently pungent aromatics.

Coffee Origin: Santa Ana growing region, El Salvador.
Bottom Line: Those who value deep, resonantly complex beverages.
Those who value floral seduction and pungent intensity in a classic Kenya.
A splendid and very characteristic Kenya, seductive yet authoritative, balanced in structure but original in aromatics.
Those who value resonance and depth in a powerful yet balanced Kenya.
Those who value a relatively gentle Kenya, sweet at the intersection of peach and flowers.
Those who value a bright, juicy version of the classic pungently sweet Kenya profile.
Those who value classic acidity and balance with a characteristic Kenya complement of chocolate, tart fruit, flowers and herb.
Those who value originality, particularly the Kenya-inflected kind: imagine the good side of sweet tomato against a backdrop of chocolate and berry.
Classic in structure, distinctively Kenya in flavor and aroma: cherry tomato and chocolate; grapefruit and black currant.

Coffee Name: Kenya AA Blue Mountain Ruita I AA
Bottom Line: A gently stated, but quite classic, Kenya: the sweetly tart, pungent black currant note softens in a cushion of dark chocolate and molasses-toned sweetness.

Coffee Origin: Ka’u growing region, Big Island of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Those who value an explicitly but lightly and elegantly ferment-toned coffee: think oranges and fine brandy.
A very delicate, cider-toned version of the natural or dried-in-the-fruit profile. May particularly appeal to those who enjoy coffees with a vibrant though softly, roundly stated acidity.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia Province, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy the syrupy mouthfeel and pungent, unorthodox aroma and flavor of a fine Sumatra.
Those who value sweetly bright, cleanly delicate coffees with fine balance and citrus, nut and floral vivacity.
Those who value a moderately dark-roasted version of the flowers and pungent berry sweetness of a good Kenya.
Those who value purity, lucidity and intricacy in a great floral-and-citrus Yirgacheffe cup.

Coffee Name: Life Saver Guatemala Organic Finca Santa Rita
Bottom Line: Those who value sweetness, balance and classic grace in a fine Central-America style coffee produced with impeccable attention to the environment.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia Region, Sidamo growing region, south-central Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who value balance and subtlety.
Those who value quiet excitement and delicate thrills.

Coffee Origin: Hambela district, Oromia growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Lovers of big, fruit-toned California cabernets and those coffee drinkers who value a refined but explicit sweet fruit ferment in their natural-processed coffees. Here a richly drying edge complicates the lush, rum-and-chocolate-toned fruit.

Coffee Name: Panama Don Pepe Fully Washed Geisha
Bottom Line: An aficionado’s Gesha, high-grown and uncompromising, with extraordinary depth and complexity.

Coffee Origin: Oromia, Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a sweet but brisk, zesty cup with quietly striking aromatics.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Decaf drinkers who value a clean, engagingly complex version of one of the world’s great coffee origins.
Those decaf drinkers who value a delicate but classic traditional American cup, balanced, clean, gently complex.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: The decaffeination process apparently emphasizes the caramel and aromatic wood notes and de-emphasizes fruit and flowers in this simple but crisp, satisfying decaf.
Sweetness, quietly layered flavor and soft acidity should please decaf drinkers who avoid intense acidity as well as caffeine.
Should satisfy decaf drinkers who enjoy moderately dark-roasted coffees, despite – or perhaps because of – the odd but intense aroma and flavor, heavy with pungent, woody sweetness.
A delicate but gently intense version of the great, always intricate Yirgacheffe profile.
Lovers of pure, delicate but complex beverages.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy aromatically complex beverages that are simultaneously sweet with a brisk, gently drying undercurrent.

I am tempted to particularly recommend this coffee to those who enjoy the pungent, complex aroma inside a cigar humidor or the sweeter odor of a cedar cabinet, but that may overly limit the appeal of this coffee, given that the attractive cedar note is just the beginning point of a complex, original profile.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who value an impressively refreshing, sweetly zesty, light-roasted cup.
Anyone who can afford it.
Those who enjoy the crisp resonance and chocolaty complication generated by a moderately dark roast applied to a distinctive green coffee.
Those who value quiet acidity and round, chocolaty balance.
Those who enjoy a delicately brisk, gently intricate cup.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who value syrupy but dry beverages with deep-toned, quietly exotic complication.
Outstanding choice for those who value depth, resonance, big body and low-toned but lively acidity.
Those who value smooth but brisk, dry beverages with subtly complex flavor and aroma.
A delicate, easy-drinking summery blend with a sneaky, crisply sweet intricacy.
Those who enjoy a briskly dry though lively, complex, quietly exotic cup.
Those who value a finely elegant, gentle, meadowy coffee with outstanding social and environmental credentials.
Fine balance in a quiet, graceful blend with unusually sweet citrus.
Those who enjoy a balanced, quietly lively lighter-roasted cup with a particularly elegant floral note.
Those who value classic balance and quiet completeness.
This unusual blend should please those who value full, syrupy body, low acidity and a rich, molasses-toned fruit.
Those who enjoy intense though nuanced acidity; a fine high-altitude Colombia in the classic style.

Coffee Origin: Arusha growing region, Mt. Meru, Tanzania.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy beverages that juxtapose juicy sweetness with the gently brisk and bracing.
Unique version of the great Kenya profile: intricately floral, honey-sweet, brisk but juicy.

Coffee Name: Burundi Kayanza Province Mpanga Washing Station
Bottom Line: Superb balance in a cup that combines chocolaty sweetness, bright fruit and a pleasingly dry hint of aromatic wood.
Those who value a quietly exotic cup with an unusual balance of walnut-like briskness and juicy mango-like fruit.
Those who value a richly and roundly bright cup with a pleasingly full mouthfeel and quietly exotic complexity.

Coffee Origin: Haraz (also spelled Haraaz) growing region, north-central Yemen
Bottom Line: Buy it both for the exotic origin and the exotic cup. The finest example of a Yemen to reach us in some time. Giddy, almost disconcertingly sweet complexity supported by a solid structure.
Lovers of comfort. A nicely balanced coffee with a quiet but engaging aromatic profile: nut, chocolate, a shimmer of flowers.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Finca Loma La Gloria
Coffee Origin: El Boqueron, Volcan de San Salvador, El Salvador.
Bottom Line: Don’t expect the classic, nor tropical fruit and flowers. In some respects one of a kind. A beverage analogy might be a heavily but very fragrantly hopped IPA.

Deeply expressed, fruity dark chocolate is the appeal here, along with a general impression of plush viscosity. Not a classic coffee, but a distinctive one. Excellent social and environmental credentials.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Sidama Province, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who can handle gracefully stated extravagance.
Those who prefer a balanced, softly bright version of a classic Kenya.
Those who enjoy quiet brightness and a fruit character that is simultaneously cleanly elegant and discreetly lush.
Classic Latin-American coffee, poised and delicately rich in structure, resonantly engaging in aroma and flavor.

Coffee Origin: Mantiqeiras de Minas growing region, Brazil, Brazil.
Bottom Line: Roasted to just shy of the second crack, this is not the way this coffee tasted to the Cup of Excellence jury that, on the basis of what was certainly a light-to-medium sample roast, awarded it an unprecedented score of 95. Nevertheless, at this moderately dark roast it’s a fine, elegantly chocolaty coffee with engaging hints of citrus and berry.
Lovers of the classic Latin-America cup: nothing flashy, nothing out of balance here, just a roundly and quietly complete cup.
Those who enjoy a gently tart cup with a balanced range of floral, fruit and crisp aromatic wood notes.
Those who enjoy moderately dark roasts that preserve some taste of place, in this case a characteristic Kenya pungent berry and (here a roast-influenced) dark chocolate.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, “Big Island” of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Kona is not a particularly distinctive origin to start with, and here a rather aggressive dark roast doesn’t leave much origin character behind for speculation. We do get some scorchy, buttery dark chocolate, however, and a tickle of lemon.
Exceptionally balanced, delicately complete version of the great southern Ethiopia wet-processed profile.
The fragrant musk, aromatic wood and hint of chocolate may make this unusual coffee a particularly good way to finish a dinner.
Offers extraordinary aromatic intrigue: complex, exotic, original.
Those who enjoy a richly tart, juicy cup with depth and fullness.
Splendidly balanced, quietly complete coffee: juicy, refreshing, vivacious.
A quietly exhilarating coffee with a particularly expressive, lively acidity.
Those who enjoy tart, dry beverages with engaging complexity.
Those who enjoy a spicy, delicate floral character in a nicely balanced organic/Fair-Trade coffee.

Coffee Origin: Kainantu district, Eastern Highlands Province, Papua New Guinea.
Bottom Line: A coffee that invites adjectives like smooth, svelte, supple. Peachy sweetness, crisp cacao.
Those who enjoy red table wines with lots of both fruit and oak may particularly enjoy this plump, juicy but brisk Rwanda.
Simply a fine, balanced, complete cup, as absolutely poised and pure as dried-in-the-fruit coffees get. The honey and peach notes are particularly appealing.
An unusually (and impressively) rich and resonant version of the floral and sweet-citrus Yirgacheffe wet-processed profile.

Anyone who enjoys depth, full mouthfeel and quiet complexity. Aficionados may be particularly interested in sampling a fine, tactfully light-roasted example of a dried-in-the-fruit coffee from Nicaragua, an origin that until now has never produced a high-end version of the type.

Coffee Origin: Eastern slopes of Volcan Baru, western Panama.
Bottom Line: Those who prefer gentle acidity and a roundly sweet-toned cup with quietly original aromatics and an impressive ecological back story.

Coffee Origin: Boquete growing region, Chiriqui Province, western Panama.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy delicately pure, gently bright, quietly complex coffees in the classic Panama style.
Spectacular array of aroma and flavor notes, shifting with little revelations clear to the bottom of the cup.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia Province, Indonesia.

Bottom Line: Richly sumptuous and quietly original. Displays sensation both deep and complex.
Its resonant depth and pungent berry enveloped in floral sweetness suggest the rounder, deeper style of Kenya. Should appeal to those who enjoy intensity without assertive brightness.
Those who enjoy brisk rather than bright coffees: lavender, nut and aromatic wood supported by a pleasing caramelly sweetness.
A discreet and understated edge-of-dark roast develops the chocolate and berryish fruit in this juicy Rwanda.
Those who enjoy gentle balance and delicately resonant aroma and flavor. A subtle and cleanly expressed organic/Fair Trade-certified coffee.
A striking but very accessible coffee. The combination of flowers, chocolate, sweet citrus and a pungent, incense-like note is unusual, and supported by a structure both balanced and seductive.
The sweetly bright, buttery juiciness of certain tropical fruits, balanced by refined cacao and aromatic wood notes. Distinctive and superb.
Exhilaratingly sweet and floral yet completed and balanced rendition of the great Yirgacheffe washed profile.

Coffee Origin: Piedra Candela, Chiriqui Province, far western Panama.
Bottom Line: A grand, brilliant coffee that presents both juicy seduction and challenging intensity and complexity.

Coffee Name: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Konga Zone Dry Process
Coffee Origin: Konga micro-region, Yirgacheffe growing region, south-central Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a richly and sweetly tart cup with deep-toned, complexly resonant aromatics.
Those who enjoy beverages that are both bracingly brisk and complexly floral. Dry martini drinkers, for example, or lovers of the more aromatic style of hoppy beers.

Coffee Origin: Lake Toba growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Particularly striking for its range of sensation, from lush flowers through juicy stone fruit and hints of spice and herb, supported by a complete, balanced structure. Should be a quite versatile cup, attractive both black and with whitener.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia Province, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a sweet-savory, zesty, citrusy cup.

Coffee Origin: Aceh growing region, northwestern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy depth, richness and an unusual juxtaposition of creamy sensations with crisp in a quietly dramatic cup.

Coffee Origin: Lake Toba growing region, North Indonesia Province, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Those coffee drinkers nostalgic for a hint of the old-fashioned earthy, full-bodied Sumatra cup updated in a thoroughly refined rendition: a touch earthy and fruity but sweet-toned, subtle, nuanced.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, Lake Toba, North Indonesia Province, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: A hint of the traditional foresty Sumatra character, moist fallen leaves and cedary flowers, enveloped in a balanced, softly lively structure.

Coffee Origin: Gayo or Aceh growing region, Aceh Province, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Classic wet-hulled Sumatra in the new refined mode, with the celebrated earth notes discreet, elegant, crisply cacao- and peach-toned.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia Province, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: This fine, classic wet-hulled Sumatra almost suggests Kenya with its crisp, sweetly tart, berryish richness.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia Province, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: The refined style of wet-hulled Sumatra character is very lightly and delicately expressed here, in this tartly lively, lighter-roasted rendition.

Coffee Origin: Aceh growing region, northwestern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: A sweet though dry tendency runs through this profile, animating a rather original aromatic that coffee drinkers who lean toward dry but lively white table wines and the more aromatic style of hoppy beers may particularly enjoy. A very good value for the price.

Coffee Origin: Toraja growing region, South Sulawesi, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: A combination of malty richness and gentle brightness make this an engaging version of a wet-hulled Sulawesi.

Coffee Name: Colombia Granja La Esperanza Grand Cru Mokka
Coffee Origin: Valle del Cauca growing region, Colombia.
Bottom Line: An opportunity to enjoy a very rare and distinctive yet easy-drinking variety: crisp yet lush, exotic though finally balanced.
Lovers of very pure but distinctive light-roasted coffees: fresh, breezy and meadowy.

Coffee Origin: Caranavi Province, La Paz Department, Bolivia.
Bottom Line: This quietly complex, crisply chocolate-toned cup should please those who prefer the subtle and silky to the bright and assertive in a Fair Trade- and organic-certified coffee.
Amazing version of the routinely amazing Gesha profile, as seductive as it is original.
A fine dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia profile: part yellow guava nectar, part crisp unsweetened chocolate, part sweetly shimmering floral top notes.

Coffee Origin: Kersa district, Oromia region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Grind this coffee and it will fill the house with heady sweet rum aromas, which fatten, complicate and round in the cup with continued intensity but impressive poise and elegance. An unusually explicit and successful experiment with cask-conditioned coffee.
Those who value gentle grace and subtlety in a silky, balanced cup.
A splendid, over-the-top, almost hallucinatory version of the great Gesha profile. Aficionados with substantial coffee budgets should not miss it.
A brilliant, challenging coffee, juicy and bright, thrilling to those who can handle the sweetly pungent, cleanly fruit-toned intensity.
An unusually delicate though intricate dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia. Exhilarating but subtle.
Big, grandly generous, juicy Kenya. A versatile coffee; should be a crowd-pleaser.
Those who enjoy resonance and savory-sweet complexity in a deep, vibrant version of the great Kenya profile.

Coffee Origin: Gedeo Zone, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy being seduced and dazzled.
Those who enjoy a plush, round, nectar-like cup with an edge of crisp complication.
Those who enjoy the poised balance and gentle brightness of a pure and classic Colombia.
Those who value a cleanly elegant variation on the sweet-savory resonance of Central Africa Great Lakes coffees.

Coffee Name: Papua New Guinea Ulya Wahgi Valley
Coffee Origin: Wahgi Valley, Western Highlands, Papua New Guinea.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a delicate but deeply expressed, subtly original cup.
Those who value juicy sweetness, syrupy mouthfeel and graceful balance in a very clean Burundi.
A fine variant on the dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia style, simultaneously lyrically sweet and crisply austere.
Those who enjoy a profound natural sweetness in a Fair-Trade-certified coffee. Sweeter and more delicate than a typical good Rwanda.
Those who enjoy poised delicacy and subtle complexity in a Fair Trade- and organic-certified coffee.

Coffee Origin: San Agustín growing region, Huila Department, southern Colombia
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a classically sweet and vibrantly citrusy Colombia.
An unusual opportunity to taste the celebrated Gesha profile in a very dark-roasted preparation. Think cedar-planked fruit-toned bon-bon.
Those who enjoy the tartly sweet sensations: orange marmalade, for example. The acidity here is enveloped in a rich sweetness and complicated by crisp, cinnamon-like aromatic wood.
Fine variation on the great Kenya cup, delicate but vivid with sweet flowers and tart berry.
Those who enjoy a rich, sweet-toned, deeply expressed cup; aficionados who value a particularly refined version of the classic Rwanda style.
A big, soaring, intense version of the floral and brightly fruit-toned Yirgacheffe profile.

Coffee Name: Ethiopia Natural Yirgacheffe Worka Coop Alemu
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a softly intricate coffee with crisp floral and cacao nib suggestions overlaying a lush, almost overripe fruit.
A particularly deeply expressed example of the sweet-savory, resonantly complex Rwanda cup.
A resonant coffee that particularly rewards patient drinking, allowing full disclosure of the layered depth of pungent fruit and sweet flowers.
A fine variation on the Kenya theme of juicy, berryish sweetness fused with the dry, savory and crisp. Aficionados of the classic Kenya style should particularly enjoy it.
A refined dried-in-the-fruit “natural” processed Yirgacheffe that gracefully balances crisp cacao and nut notes with complex, musky flowers.

Coffee Origin: Konga District, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: An elegant balance of dry chocolate and sweet orange and flowers animates this cleanly crisp dried-in-the-fruit Yirgacheffe.

Coffee Origin: Eastern slopes of Volcan Baru, western Panama.
Bottom Line: A classic medium roast develops an engaging and original balance of crisply dry unsweetened chocolate and sweet orange and musky, grappa-like notes.
Those who enjoy lighter-roasted, cleanly crisp, brisk coffees with quietly engaging aromatic intrigue.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia Region, Sidamo growing region, south-central Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: A superb wet-processed southern Ethiopia coffee, softly tart yet roundly juicy, with a subtle yet astounding range of aroma and flavor notes.

Coffee Origin: Cañas Verdes, Boquete growing region, western Panama.
Bottom Line: A dried-in-the-fruit Gesha with all of the depth, range and complexity of the type held in a structural matrix of accessible balance and restraint.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: This classic southern Ethiopia wet-processed profile balances floral and fresh-fruit sweetness with a crisp, cocoa-edged briskness. For those who enjoy sweetness without simplicity.
A delicate but complete version of the great Kenya profile, elegant in its juxtaposition of sweet, honeyish fruit and flowers with a lightly brisk, gently drying mouthfeel.

Coffee Name: Honduras Santa Barbara Las Brisas, Denis Teruel
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a gently pungent, resonant Central America cup with pleasing mouthfeel and distinct chocolate.
A quiet but still vivacious and distinctive version of the rare and always surprising Gesha profile.

Coffee Origin: Konga District, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: The slightly fermenty, cidery note complicates a pleasingly light and lively fruit-and-flowers profile. Lovers of delicately fruity but crisp white wines should particularly enjoy this cup.
A particularly deep and complex version of the great wet-processed Yirgacheffe profile: The incense-like aromatic wood note gives resonance and depth to the pungent fruit and lush flowers.

Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, “Big Island” of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Big, ringing, classic coffee. The Bourbon trees of Central and South America probably first gave North American culture the archetype of the classic coffee, with its sweet, juicy brightness, full mouthfeel, and richly layered flavor. Here the Bourbon-derived East Africa SL28 variety brought half-way around the world to Hawaii returns to this classic profile.
The floral, cocoa and crisply sweet citrus character of a classic Yirgacheffe at a very good price.
Those who enjoy the peculiar intensity of certain Kenya coffees, in which a very sweet yet dry berry note dominates in a profile simultaneously juicy and tartly brisk.
Those who enjoy a classically sweet, pungently bright, vivaciously lively Kenya.

Coffee Origin: Valle del Cauca growing region, Colombia.
Bottom Line: A richly low-toned, chocolate-and-nut-nuanced cup with impressive social and environmental credentials.
An extraordinary version of an extraordinary origin: intense and distinctive, yet poised, suave, balanced.

This great dried-in-the-fruit Gesha displays solid, flawless structure and stunningly intricate aromatics. Particularly engaging is the way the lush fruit works against spicier and drier notes like the unsweetened chocolate and tea rose.

It’s hard to imagine a more table-pleasingly versatile holiday coffee than this smooth, round, yet exhilaratingly complex blend, but aficionados also may find it worth seeking out for its complex expression of the classic Bourbon style.

Coffee Origin: Gedeo zone, Yirgacheffe growing region, south-central Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who can handle an almost impossibly sweet, lavishly fruit-toned coffee ringing with symphonic complexity.
An exceptional choice for the lovers of richly complex, pleasingly bittersweet beverages; bitters-heavy mixed drinks and cocktails, to offer only one example.
Those who enjoy mulled wine or similar beverages that merge the tart, the sweet and the savory may particularly enjoy this unusual blend.

Coffee Origin: San Fernando, Nueva Segovia region, Nicaragua.
Bottom Line: Those who prefer richness and low-toned intricacy in a coffee with a distinctive sensory profile and big, dramatic beans.
Brings an appropriately savory-sweet, spicy presence to the holiday cup.
Lovers of the richly and sweetly bright; a classic cup on steroids.
The engaging juxtaposition of sweet and dry tendencies in this seasonal blend resolve with particularly satisfying richness in an unusually long and complex finish.
A curiosity from close to home, this first-ever California-grown coffee is impressively balanced, deep and quietly intricate.

A Kenya for aficionados, with the deep, sweetly tart, slightly savory structure of the style supporting a distinctive set of aromatics. The interesting tobacco note suggests the fragrantly fruity style of tobacco called perique.
Those who enjoy quiet complexity in a low-toned though resonant classic Guatemala cup.
Fireworks and subtle grace in a striking cup that should both comfort and excite.
A very light-roasted presentation encourages contemplation of a dried-in-the-fruit green coffee as absolutely pure as it is vibrant and intricate.
A particularly fine, floral-toned version of the classic Kenya profile, delicate and giddy in its sweet flowers and berry working over drier, more savory suggestions.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: An engagingly lush yet cleanly crisp, intricately layered version of the great Ethiopia natural or dried-in-the-fruit cup.

Coffee Origin: Tarrazu growing region, central Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: hose who enjoy classic coffees with a round, deep, syrupy profile and quiet complexity.
Light roasting develops the delicate, refreshing, very gently tart character of this coffee. The distinct pear-like notes, crisp yet juicy, are particularly attractive and unusual.

Coffee Origin: Toraja growing region, south-central Sulawesi, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Those who prefer the low-toned exotic in a round, resonant cup.
Those who value the rather rough, earthy style of Indonesian coffees.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica La Nena Red Honey
Coffee Origin: Central Valley growing region, Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: An attractive coffee for those who prefer naturally sweet coffees with quiet acidity but gently lively aromatics.

Coffee Origin: Kochere, Yirgacheffe growing region, south-central Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy the intense, complex flowers and tart, sweet vivacity of a classic Yirgacheffe.
Knock-out Sumatra. As elegant as it is earthy and exotic.
A straightforward, refreshing cup in the traditional American breakfast coffee mode.

Coffee Origin: Konga District, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy big, fruity red table wines. This is a dried-in-the-fruit coffee that makes no apologies for its lush, brandy-soaked sweetness.
Those who enjoy the engagingly different in coffee. This is not a typical Kenya, but it is certainly a pleasing and distinctive one.

Coffee Origin: Wahgi Valley, Western Highlands, Papua New Guinea.
Bottom Line: A subtly original coffee that rewards patience. A fine choice for those who prefer quiet, nuanced depth to assertive brightness.

Coffee Origin: Valle de Cauca Department, southwestern Colombia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy quiet balance in a classic lighter-roasted Latin-American breakfast cup.

Coffee Origin: San Marcos, Tarrazu growing region, central Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a classic American breakfast cup with quietly rounded acidity and pleasing nuance.
Extraordinary coffee, intense yet balanced, supporting a giddy avalanche of aromatic complexity.

Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, “Big Island” of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: A classic coffee, grandly structured but balanced, with a massive but gracefully expressed range of aroma and flavor.

Coffee Origin: San Fernando, Nueva Segovia region, Nicaragua.
Bottom Line: Those who prefer depth and resonance to brightness in an engagingly complex coffee.

Coffee Origin: El Salto, Boquete growing region, Panama.
Bottom Line: Lush and complex in flavor and aroma, crisp and bittersweet in structure, a remarkable cup for coffee adventurers patient enough to navigate its layered intricacy.
A fine variation on the great Gesha fruit, flower and cacao complex, supported by a structure simultaneously crisp and syrupy.
Light roasting allows this Pacamara’s gently unusual character full expression.

Coffee Origin: Cañas Verdes, Boquete growing region, western Panama.
Bottom Line: A fine variation on the great Gesha profile, with the full suite of Gesha aromatics, but showing a bit more chocolate and less floral than is typical for this distinguished variety.

Coffee Origin: Valle del Cauca growing region, Colombia.
Bottom Line: Some may prefer this quieter version of the Gesha cup; still exotic and complex, but a bit more chocolate, fewer flowers, less forward acidity. And for a coffee this distinguished and this close in expression to the famous and rare Gesha, an excellent value: in other words, quite a bit of Geshaness for relatively little money.
A quiet but vibrant rendition of the great Kenya SL 28 profile: juicy, gently pungent, with a shimmer of backgrounded flowers.
Those aficionados interested in sampling a particularly fine version of the huge-beaned Maracaturra.

Coffee Name: Imperial Reserve Juan Pena La Papaya Washed
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a pure, subtle, gently sweet-toned cup.
Those who appreciate big, sweet, resonating brightness and layered nuance in a superb Kenya.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Fine choice for lovers of the traditional earthy Sumatra cup who want an upgrade to a, well, elegantly earthy Sumatra cup.
Those who enjoy crisply dry, spice- and floral-toned white table wines.
Those who prefer bittersweetness and depth to tart brightness in a classic medium-roast cup.
A balanced, quietly complete coffee that gracefully embodies the softly pungent, sweetly seductive tendencies associated with the classic Guatemala Antigua cup.
Those who enjoy crisply sweet, delicate coffees alive with floral, nut and fresh-cut aromatic wood notes.
A fine choice for those who enjoy a coffee with a roast note that complements without overwhelming the underlying character of the coffee.
The honey processing and a darkish medium roast together develop an almost Sumatra-like fusion of sweet fruit, aromatic wood, deep, perfumy flowers and a hint of clay-like earth.
Those who appreciate the powerful but sweet acidity of a very pure, finely nuanced Kenya.

Coffee Origin: Gedeo Zone, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: An unusually deep and dessert-like version of the great fruit-and-flowers Yirgacheffe profile.

Coffee Origin: Gedeo Zone, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Delicate, lemony and floral, sweet yet dry, this coffee may particularly appeal to lovers of analogous styles of white table wines.
Those who love the sweet, juicy intensity of big acidity, in this case wrapped in the resonance of complex floral, chocolate and bright fruit.
A pleasingly pungent and crisp version of the great Yirgacheffe profile; here deep-toned cocoa, nut and berry move forward, backgrounding the still lively floral notes.
A tactfully roast-rounded Kenya: gently bright, gracefully nuanced, chocolaty.
A quiet but complex and original Kenya that should please those who prefer resonance to assertive brightness.

Coffee Origin: Konga District, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Lovers of cognacs and fine American rye and corn whiskies may particularly enjoy this big, sweetly dry, complex coffee.
A balanced structure supports a particularly sweet, graceful rendition of Yirgacheffe flowers, citrus and chocolate.
Classic American cup: bright but sweet, balanced, engaging, breakfasty.
Those who enjoy delicate but authoritative beverages. Should make a very fine, refreshing iced coffee.
The quiet complexity and balanced resonance characteristic of this fine hybrid variety.
A brisk, delicately lively coffee for fall mornings.
Complete, balanced version of a blend with an inspiring story and a good cause. A fat, deep resonance of sensation is perhaps its most striking sensory feature.

Coffee Origin: Valle de Cauca Department, western Colombia
Bottom Line: Those who prefer the deep, low-toned, chocolaty style of Colombia coffee.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: An excellent choice for upscaling Sumatra lovers as well as anyone who enjoys an exotic cup, simultaneously lush yet crisp.

Coffee Origin: Gedeo Zone, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a dramatically aromatic and crisply refreshing cup.
Fine example of the great Kenya profile: complex, sweet though dry, juicy but grown-up.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Extraordinarily sweetly bright and refreshing cup, a spring morning in September.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Cerro San Luis Honey
Coffee Origin: San Luis de Grecia, central Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Those who value a combination of floral sweetness and crisp, nutty chocolate in a balanced, quietly rich cup.
A superb coffee in virtually every respect, grandly structured and original in aromatics, with a fine balance between honey-like sweetness and pungent and tart notes.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy the new style of Sumatra, still rich and deep, but elegant and refined in its chocolate, pungent citrus and aromatic wood character.

Coffee Origin: Ka'u growing district, "Big Island" of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: A very light-roasted, flawlessly prepared coffee for those who value purity, silken delicacy and fresh, crisp aromatics.

Coffee Name: Colombia Granja La Esperanza Grand Cru Mokka

Bottom Line: Aficionados interested in enjoying a delicate, subtly exotic version of the very rare Mokka variety of Arabica; anyone who values subtlety, purity and balance in the cup.
A fine, elegantly complex dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia profile, with particularly complex floral notes and just a hint of rum-like spirits.
Those who enjoy delicate balance in a finely structured, quietly complex cup.

Anyone who can afford it. The wet-processed Gesha profile, however complex and extraordinary, can be too bright and drying for many coffee drinkers, but here the dried-in-the-fruit or natural processing rounds and deepens the acidity – and everything else – in this utterly amazing, if dauntingly expensive, coffee.

Coffee Name: Panama Estate Reserve: Elida Estate Natural
Bottom Line: Christmas in September. The dark chocolate, ripe fruit and hints of mint and warm spice suggest holiday pleasures.

Aficionados may enjoy sampling an unusual variety and its enormous beans, but everyone with a refined coffee sweet tooth should enjoy the natural sweetness and tropical fruit (and drink) suggestions proposed by aroma and flavor.

Coffee Name: Panama Chiriqui Finca Santa Teresa Geisha
Bottom Line: Those interested in sampling the giddy intricacy of the Gesha profile in its unusual honey-process incarnation.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Cerro San Luis Natural
Coffee Origin: San Luis de Grecia, central Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Crisp cacao nib and cedar suggestions balance gently lush lily and brandy in this finely understated dried-in-the-fruit profile.
Meditative coffee lovers. This quiet but balanced and subtle dried-in-the-fruit coffee encourages patient, attentive drinking.

Coffee Origin: Los Robles de Naranjo, West Valley, Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy sweetness and delicacy without simplicity.
Cabernet drinkers in particular may enjoy this big, rich honey-processed cup.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Las Lajas Perla Negra Natural
Coffee Origin: Central Valley growing region, Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Those who prefer depth, resonance and balance to bright assertion in a quietly nuanced cup.

Coffee Origin: Volcan de Santa Ana region, El Salvador.
Bottom Line: The sweet yet dry fruit character of Bourbon-derived varieties of Arabica presents here with subtle understatement that should please those who value gentle acidity, full mouthfeel and quietly distinctive aromatics.

Coffee Origin: San Ignacio Acosta, Tarrazu growing region, central Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Sophisticated flowers and chocolate, crisp and suave.
A very complete coffee; its natural, chocolaty sweetness may make it a good choice for those interested in transitioning from sweetener and whitener to taking their coffee black.
A classic Kenya, elegantly dry yet sweetly juicy, floral, chocolaty.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Las Mercedes Pacamara Honey
Bottom Line: Anyone who enjoys complex essays in juxtapositions of sweet and savory should enjoy this coffee, but aficionados may be particularly interested in possible readings of impact of variety and processing method: The savory/sweet richness may be owing to the impact of the Pacamara variety; the honey processing doubtless further contributes to sweetness and complexity.
Those who enjoy big body and deep, low-toned complexity in a versatile cup.

Coffee Origin: Aceh growing region, northwestern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Adventurers who enjoy exotic variations on the old-fashioned syrupy, earthy (here pipe-tobaccoish) Sumatra cup.
A brisk but sweet, juicy rendition of the great Kenya profile.

Coffee Origin: Ka'u growing district, "Big Island" of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: An exquisitely pure, very light-roasted coffee. Lovers of fine Rieslings and similar fresh, floral-toned white table wines should particularly enjoy this cup.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, “Big Island” of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: A splendid organically grown Kona that manages to be deep yet delicate, and utterly pure in its peach and floral nuance.

Coffee Origin: Ka'u growing district, "Big Island" of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Elegant and Kenya-like in its intensity and suggestions of pungent berryish fruit and lush flowers.

Coffee Name: High Mountain Io Fancy Light Roast
Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, “Big Island” of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Quiet but lively acidity and a wide range of appealing aromatics – honey, citrus, chocolate, hints of spice and flowers – make this an appealing rendition of the classic Kona cup.
Those who enjoy a lushly deep but delicate cup from a singular and surprising Hawaii origin.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, “Big Island” of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a quietly distinguished Kona cup: roundly balanced, not too acidy, grapey, chocolaty.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, “Big Island” of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Chocolate and rich flowers should please those who enjoy a Kona cup with gentle acidity and deep-toned, musky aromatics.

Curious aficionados and those who value the quietly exotic. We puzzled over the odd sweet/sour/savory structure of this coffee when we cupped it blind. Such complications can be generated by serendipitous accidents of fruit removal and drying. We hope, however, that they are related to botanical variety, since this sample was produced from trees of a rare and unusual hybrid developed by Hawaii-based scientist Chifumi Nagai that combines the distinctive-tasting Mokka variety, probably originally from Yemen or Ethiopia via Brazil, and a sturdy local strain of the classic Typica.

Coffee Origin: Aleta Wondo, Sidama growing region, Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a briskly bright but honeyish sweet cup.
A square-on medium roast develops the depth and cedary chocolate of this fine Panama.
Kenya balance and contrast – an elegant combination of dry, crisp, almost savory sensations enveloped in sweetness – is impressively on display here.

Coffee Name: Harfusa Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Fair Trade Organic
Bottom Line: A very pure and accessible rendition of the delicate, precious floral and sweet citrus Yirgacheffe cup.

Coffee Origin: Boke, Gamo Gofa Zone, Southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: A very exciting coffee, pure but exotic. The subtly layered floral and fruit notes are lyric and original.
A classic Kenya, elegantly dry yet sweetly juicy and chocolate-toned.
A balanced, complete structure supports a refreshing, sweetly citrusy aromatic.

Cautious coffee adventurers. Here the dried-in-the-fruit or “natural” processing produces a soft, complex, rather chocolaty cup free of the fermenty, brandy-like notes often associated with the natural Ethiopia cup.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy deeply and complexly expressed acidity, in this case a chorus of sweet, bitter, tart and savory sensations. Not a particularly easy or comfortable coffee, but an exciting one.
Those who enjoy a naturally sweet, light-roasted coffee that brings a whiff of meadows and morning into the cup.
Here the round, balanced structure for which Panamas are famous supports an exhilarating display of juicy fruit suggestions, opulent flowers, and a hint of whiskey.
Those who enjoy big, intense coffees expressing great range in structure and aromatics, from sweet flowers through complex fruit to savory hints of herb.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Helsar Manuel Macho Arce
Coffee Origin: West Valley growing region, Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy grace and subtle originality in a gentle, syrupy cup.
Those who enjoy a delicate but sweet and brightly lively breakfast cup.

A Sumatra both refined and intense; those many lovers of the Sumatra type should not miss this one; purists who still remain suspicious of the type should find this example both familiar (the pungent fruit is almost Kenya-like) yet original: pipe tobacco, clay, richly fudgy chocolate.

Coffee Origin: Kochere, Yirgacheffe growing region, south-central Ethiopia.

Classically big, juicy, brandy-toned dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia for those many coffee drinkers who love the style.
Classic Kenya; almost perfectly structured and finely nuanced around sweetly tart fruit and fragrant floral suggestions.
Those who prefer a gentle but lively and engaging breakfast cup.

Coffee Origin: Kochere, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a delicately lively, briskly floral- and honey-toned cup.
This sweet, deep, floral-toned cup, particularly characteristic of the best Rwandas, should please those who enjoy a pure but exotically complex coffee.
Those who prefer richness, resonance and chocolate to purity and brightness in a lighter roasted coffee. Good environmental and socio-economic credentials.
Those who enjoy a very sweet cup deepened by a savory edge.
Those who enjoy sweetly dry, slightly savory beverages, in this case complicated by some unusual aromatic intrigue.
The unusual juxtaposition of brisk, cedary black tea notes with lush ripe fruit and floral sweetness is original and attractive.

Coffee Origin: Agua Dulce, Huehuetenango growing region, Guatemala.

A deep, resonant version of the great floral and citrus Yirgacheffe cup.
A relaxed, balanced, straightforward breakfast cup.

Bottom Line: A fine example of the latest style of Ethiopia dried-in-the-fruit cup: the fruit delicately lush and clean, the flowers sweet and exhilarating, the whisky-like hint enlivening but discreet.

Those who prefer depth and resonance to brightness and drama in a balanced breakfast cup.

Coffee Origin: Toraja growing region, south-central Sulawesi, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy pungently sweet beverages.

Coffee Origin: Eastern Highlands Province, Papua New Guinea
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a balanced, quietly complex breakfast cup animated by brisk but juicily sweet suggestions of ripe grapefruit.

Coffee Origin: Upper Asaro Valley, Eastern Papua New Guinea.
Bottom Line: Almost Kenya-like in its sweet, exhilarating acidity and pungent berry suggestions, though approached in any context a fine coffee.

Coffee Origin: Toraja growing region, South Sulawesi, Indonesia

Coffee Origin: Toraja growing region, southwestern Sulawesi, Indonesia

Coffee Origin: Wahgi Valley, Western Highlands, Papua New Guinea.
Bottom Line: Those who prefer depth and resonance to assertion and brightness in a complex, well-structured cup.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Sidama Province, southern Ethiopia.

Those to whom an unusual flavor complex, sweet but pungent, deep-toned, slightly spicy, appeals.

Coffee Origin: Santa Maria de Dota valley, Tarrazu growing region, Costa Rica.

Those who enjoy low acidity and chocolate and nut notes in a certified organically-grown coffee.

Coffee Origin: San Agustín growing region, Huila Department, southern Colombia
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy sweet yet pungently deep and nut-toned profiles.
Balance and elegance in a superb classic Kenya.

Coffee Origin: Celinga Village, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Simply a superb coffee in the washed southern Ethiopia style, lyric and exhilarating.
Those who enjoy a delicately exotic, crisp yet sweet breakfast cup.
A strong-structured coffee with a syrupy but dry mouthfeel and pronounced but rounded acidity.

Coffee Origin: Matas de Minas growing region, Brazil, Brazil.

Coffee Origin: Timana growing region, Huila Department, southern Colombia
Bottom Line: A distinctive variation on the classic Colombia profile, juicy with a crisp, engaging savory edge.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Sidama Province, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy gentle complexity and balance and a bit of savory/cidery intrigue.

Quietly complete cup with a slight spice hint to the flowers. Expresses the combination of delicacy and sensory depth traditionally associated with the Tanzania peaberry, a classic coffee type particularly prominent in the early decades of the North American specialty coffee movement.

Those who enjoy coffees sweet and pure enough to achieve completeness in a very light roasting style.

Lovers of the flamboyantly fruit-and-spirits style of dried-in-the-fruit coffee, intoxicating and complex, dusk in a tropical forest. Not for coffee purists.

Complete in structure and exotic in detail: honey and spice in a lush, syrupy-bodied cup.
Unusual and attractive profile, with a bracing grapefruity brightness enveloped in honey and flowers.
Those who enjoy their chocolate with complications, both savory and floral.
Those who enjoy big-bodied, richly acidy coffees with resonantly original aromatics, grapey and complexly floral.
Lovers of originality, in this case driven by paradox: crisply savory nut enveloped in honey-and-floral sweetness.

Bottom Line: Brisk but lush profile for those who enjoy both balance and excitement.
Those who prefer resonant sweetness and gentle complexity in a versatile, all-day cup.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia Region, Sidama Province, Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Lovers of grand sensory gestures; Cirque du Soleil in a cup.

Coffee Origin: Sul de Minas growing region, southern Brazil, Brazil.

Fine balance in a roundly tart but very sweet profile.
The deep, resonant sweetness of night-blooming flowers in particular permeates this soft, melodic coffee.
Those who value poise and balance in a delicately structured, sweetly fragrant cup.
Those who enjoy the big, rich style of Colombia cup, with the chocolaty sweetness balanced by a crisp cedary edge.

Coffee Origin: Valle del Cauca growing region, Colombia.

Fine and original variant on the dried-in-the-fruit cup, preserving the pungent, complex sweetness of the type with little of the usual fermenty fruit.

Bottom Line: Those who enjoy quiet distinction, depth and resonance in a versatile, all-day cup.

Bottom Line: An extraordinary bargain: offers a persuasive version of the sensory fireworks of a great Gesha at about one-fifth the price.
A gentle but distinctively engaging breakfast cup with Fair Trade and organic credentials.
Delicate but sweetly and crisply engaging breakfast cup with impressive social and environmental credentials.
Cacao-nib crisp but amaretto-like sweet, resonantly complex, a superb version of the dried-in-the-fruit southern Ethiopia type.
A hint of clean ferment contributes a whisky-like shimmer to the complex fruit and floral notes of this impressive dried-in-the-fruit coffee.
A fine variation on the sweet and berryish yet crisply dry-boned Kenya profile.
Crisp delicacy and vanilla and floral tones that could add up to lily may make this breakfast blend particularly suitable for Easter-time spring mornings.
Solid structure and deep, exotic aromatics should both reassure and surprise at breakfast.
An extravagant yet crisply focused coffee; a fine morning surprise.
Those who know and enjoy Sumatra coffees should particularly enjoy this moderately dark-roasted, briskly complex variation on the Indonesian wet-hulled cup.

Coffee Name: Brazil Yellow Catuai Esperança Joao “Zinho” Souza
Bottom Line: Those who value delicacy without loss of complexity.

Coffee Origin: Carmo de Minas growing region, Brazil, Brazil
Bottom Line: Definitely not purists; rather those who enjoy the lush, edgily overripe fruit and floral sweetness of an old-fashioned dried-in-the-fruit coffee.

Coffee Origin: Sao Sebastiao da Grama, Sao Paulo state, south-central Brazil.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a measure of tart authority in a crisp, cacao-toned Brazil.

Coffee Origin: Matas de Minas growing region, Brazil, Brazil.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy spicy flowers and near-incense-like pungency, softened by a more familiar chocolaty cacao-nib note.

Coffee Origin: Carmo de Minas growing region, Brazil, Brazil
Bottom Line: Lovers of subtle dessert-like flavors in coffee.

Coffee Origin: Dom Vicoso, Minas Gerais state, east-central Brazil.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy balance and subtle, layered complexity. The chocolate note is particularly pure and delicate.

Coffee Name: Brazil Leuven Santa Margarida Estate Lot 129
Bottom Line: The soft acidity of a classic Brazil combined with authority in structure and engaging aroma and flavor. When it is next available, aficionados will definitely want to sample this coffee to tease out the sensory impact of adding wine yeast to the vat during the fermentation step, as well as to experience what in our records is the lightest roasted coffee ever tested at Coffee Review, certainly the only one close to this light to score so well.
The sweet sage note in particular deepens and adds nuance to this fine, deeply-expressed version of the Bourbon-influenced Central Africa cup.

Coffee Name: Gelgelu Adame Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Organic Natural Process
Bottom Line: A dried-in-the-fruit Yirgacheffe for purists: cleanly and grandly opulent.
Those who enjoy an aromatically straightforward though roundly big-bodied cup at an affordable price.
The impact of decaffeination drains aromatics from this solid, good-value coffee, but leaves a pleasingly full, syrupy mouthfeel and a fresh, woody sweetness.

Coffee Origin: Toraja growing region, South Sulawesi, Indonesia
Bottom Line: An unusual overlap of ripe, slightly savory tomato and sweet, vanilla-like flowers animates this distinctive coffee.

Clean, delicate vivacity should please any coffee drinker, but aficionados may be particularly interested in sampling a coffee produced in Latin America from a distinctive coffee variety closely associated with East Africa.
A classic Colombia in the traditional style: bright but sweet and balanced; complete without flourishes or drama. Classic breakfast-cup drinkers should enjoy it.
Round, low-toned coffee that rewards patient drinking with an oaky, chocolaty depth.

Coffee Origin: Gedeo Zone, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those interested in a cleanly expressed yet triumphantly intricate example of the dried-in-the-fruit or “natural” Ethiopia profile. Extraordinary value for the money.
Those who enjoy coffees that insist on being noticed.
Extraordinary coffee with the always astounding Kenya fusion of big, berry-toned sweetness with crisp, dry authority and aromatic depth and complexity.
Those who enjoy syrupy mouthfeel and resonant, low-toned complexity.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Coffee adventurers looking for quiet excitement. Unusual aroma and flavor, lush but crisp, cidery.
Try it for the distinct toffee-like character haloed by a rather deep, sweet floral note and pungent fir.
Those who enjoy a quietly lively cup from a relatively rare origin.
Very sweet but superbly balanced structure and deep, engaging aromatics should please nearly everyone.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy refreshingly clean, whisky-toned fruit in the more balanced style of dried-in-the-fruit cup.
Those who enjoy white wines that that are both crisply dry and delicately and sweetly floral.

Coffee Name: Honduras Santa Barbara Beneficio San Vicente Caracolillo
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a classic but distinctive breakfast cup, zesty yet plush.

Classic Kenya. Balanced in structure but with the Kenya aroma/flavor complex on steroids. If you don’t know Kenyas, try this one. If you do know Kenyas and you like them, don’t miss this one. Spectacular.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Santa Elena Honey Pacamara
Bottom Line: A classically bright cup enveloped in sweetness and heady aromatics. A breakfast cup with a major aromatic bonus.
Those who enjoy the natural sweetness and exhilarating citrus and flowers of a classic Yirgacheffe.
Lovers of light, dry white table wines.
Those who enjoy a honey-toned, complexly refreshing morning cup.
Those who enjoy a sweetly brisk, citrusy morning cup.
Those many coffee drinkers who enjoy a round, gently complex, sweetly chocolaty cup.
Those who prefer depth and complex chocolaty sweetness to the brighter, brisker, cleaner pleasures of many third-wave drip coffees.
Distinctive but versatile blend (pleasing with whitener or without) with a wide stance: simultaneously displays a lemony brightness, blueberry and chocolate sweetness, and a savory musk.
Those who enjoy balance, delicacy and subtle complexity in a classic American-style breakfast cup.
Adventurers with a sweet tooth.
Those who enjoy depth and resonance in a cup that complicates seductive sweetness with a savory pungency.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: A crisply (and skillfully) light-roasted version of the fruit-and-brandy style of southern Ethiopia natural-processed cup.
Those who enjoy gently bracing, sweet-toned acidity in beverages, as displayed in certain dry white table wines, for example. This sensation is elegantly and complexly expressed here.
An unusually deep and resonantly authoritative version of the Yirgacheffe cup; the flowers are still there, but they show an almost carnal richness.
Quietly unusual cup with its foresty suggestions of dusk flowers and fresh wet wood.
Fresh, sweet, gently spicy wood notes complicated by lily and peach should please those who prefer to be coddled rather than jolted awake by their morning cup.

Coffee Origin: Borena Zone, Yirgacheffe growing region, souther Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: A particularly spicy and rich version of the great Yirgacheffe profile; sounds like the holidays to us.
Those who value both balance and intensity in a quietly distinctive Kenya.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, Big Island of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Slightly darkish medium roast develops the chocolate in a round, deep, plump-bodied version of the Kona cup.
Exhilarating range of sensation in this moderately dark-roasted Yirgacheffe, ranging from perfumy lilac to juniper-like pungency.
Anyone who can afford this soaringly complex yet perfectly structured cup. Brew this precious coffee carefully.
Delicately, refreshingly brisk yet sweetly floral version of the great Kenya profile.
Those holiday blend buyers who value a lighter roasted coffee that emphasizes with elegance and tact the honey, floral and cocoa side of the holiday culinary myth.
Those who enjoy the newer refined style of Sumatra: deep, exotic, but balanced.

Coffee Name: Original Christmas, Nicks Holiday Favorite, Organic
Bottom Line: Holidays for sure here: fruit, spice, brandy, big body.
The out-front and expressive fruit, brandy and flowers that dominate cup and aroma should make a nice fit with holiday brunches and desserts.

Coffee Name: Panama Finca La Mula Geisha Natural
Bottom Line: The aromatic fireworks are crisp and balanced in this version of the celebrated Gesha profile. The clean dried-in-the-fruit processing contributes a delightfully refreshing apple cider note.
Superb balance, complete structure and deeply expressed aroma and flavor should impress aficionados while seducing any casual coffee drinkers around the holiday table.
An aficionado’s essay in the pleasures of big, resonant, lavishly sweet acidity and simple but deeply expressed aroma and flavor.
An amazing coffee, with an immense range and depth of sensation.

Those who enjoy the deep, richly pungent, fruit-toned but slightly savory side of the Kenya profile. Lovers of big, complexly balanced red table wines may be particularly good candidates for this coffee.

Coffee Origin: Dolok Sanggul, Lintong growing area, northern Indonesia, Indonesia
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a complex, rather exotic cup dominated by molasses-like sweetness, tropical fruit and a hint of spice.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Finca Malacara Lot B
Coffee Origin: Volcan de Santa Ana region, El Salvador.
Bottom Line: A light roast develops a sweet yet crisply drying cup with delicate, unusual aromatics.
This roundly deep, chocolaty blend should provide considerable rich winter inspiration.
Precious, delicate, refined, with a quietly layered complexity.
Richly floral variant on the great Kenya profile offers complex structure, big but balanced acidity, plush mouthfeel.

Coffee Origin: Wahgi Valley, central Papua New Guinea.
Bottom Line: Those aficionados and others interested in sampling the roundly pungent fruit and rich coherence of a classic Papua New Guinea cup.

Coffee Origin: Konga District, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Fine and distinctive version of the newer dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia style, with a slight shimmer of ferment enlivening a richly and cleanly floral- and cacao-toned cup.
Those who enjoy a crisply dry but complexly juicy, fruit-toned cup.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Unusually deep and syrupy expression of the southern Ethiopian floral cup.
Those who enjoy depth and savory-sweet resonance in a classic Guatemala cup.
Briskly juicy, pleasingly syrupy Kenya.
Those who enjoy a gracefully balanced, refreshing cup with quiet aromatic intrigue.
A fine traditional-style darker-roasted Sumatra for those who enjoy the hearty but nuanced earth, smoke and chocolate of the style.
Those who enjoy a gentle morning cup, low in acidity, balanced, unassuming and agreeable in character and aromatics.
Those who enjoy history and hearty coffee with a deep, savory complexity.
Those who enjoy the juxtaposition of berry and chocolate sweetness and tart, dry elegance of a fine Kenya.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Unusually bright and citrusy version of the dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia cup should please classicists.

Coffee Origin: Gedeo Zone, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a quiet, cleanly understated version of the gently fermenty, dried-in-the-fruit cup.
A light roast develops the natural sweetness and crisp richness of this cleanly balanced dried-in-the-fruit coffee.

Coffee Origin: Gedeo Zone, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: An outstanding version of the more brandy-like style of dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia coffees. The fermented notes are sweet, graceful and cleanly expressed.

A lighter-roasted dried-in-the-fruit coffee that balances great purity and clarity of structure with delicately lush aromatics. Perhaps may satisfy those clean-cup fanatics willing to at least experiment with dried-in-the-fruit profiles.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: A nicely conducted extreme light roast develops the lyric sweetness and delicate complexity of this very pure dried-in-the-fruit coffee. Those who enjoy sophisticated lagers with floral-toned hops might be particular candidates for this one.

Coffee Origin: Gedeo Zone, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Environmentally and socially conscious hedonists. A lush, voluptuous, but cleanly structured dried-in-the-fruit coffee with the chocolate, flowers and brandy appeal of the type plus Fair Trade and organic certifications.

A hint of blueberry- and whisky-toned ferment complicates floral and chocolate aromatics, all supported by almost perfect structure. A striking value; one seldom sees a coffee this distinctive and distinguished at such a reasonable price.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: For those who can afford it, a coffee flawlessly balanced and deeply exotic in its resonance and complexity.
Classic Guatemala: soft without simplicity, perfectly balanced, enveloping chocolate and low-acid fruit.
Honey and almonds and silky, lyric mouthfeel in this fine certified variant on the great Yirgacheffe cup.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, "Big Island" of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: A classic Kona, quietly complete, gently seductive.
A solid version of the celebrated Jamaica Blue Mountain profile, with good low-toned fruit and chocolate.

Coffee Origin: Baringo and Nakura Counties, central Kenya.
Bottom Line: Those who value the pungently dry yet sweet berry character of a classic Kenya.
An aficionado’s Kenya, striking in its grand, expressive acidity and dry berry and floral elegance.
The Gesha aromatic fireworks in an unusually suave and balanced package.

Coffee Name: Panama Los Lajones Bambu Geisha Natural
Bottom Line: Exhilarating Gesha fireworks in a brisk, silky cup.

Coffee Name: 100% Kona High Mountain Io Extra Fancy
Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, Hawaii.
Bottom Line: A classic cup in a big, deeply and complexly expressed, lushly tart style suggested but seldom achieved by fine Konas.

Coffee Name: Honduras El Cielito Finca Las Brisas
Bottom Line: Purity, balance and a quietly lively complexity in an impressive Central-America-style cup.
Deep, complexly original blend echoes many of the Thanksgiving season’s sensory themes.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Superb Sumatra: juicy yet richly earthy; distinctive but balanced.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Sonora Estate Honey Valencia
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy classic coffees with an exotic edge.

Coffee Origin: Eastern slopes of Volcan Baru, western Panama.
Bottom Line: Crisp, exhilarating dried-in-the-fruit profile, with the sweet ferment suggestions refined and subtle.
Those who enjoy brisk, delicate coffees with exhilarating aromatics.

Coffee Origin: Gedeo Zone, Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: A style of richly and sweetly fermenty dried-in-the-fruit or “natural” coffee that now seems almost old-fashioned, given the progress producers have made in reducing the fruit-ferment note in dried-in-the-fruit coffees. The salty or bitter finish that often mars such richly fermenty coffees is absent here, however, so if you know you like the style, this coffee is an outstanding choice.
Those who enjoy gently dry, nut-toned coffees; aficionados interested in sampling a nicely roasted permutation of an interesting hybrid variety.
The great exhilaratingly floral and citrusy Yirgacheffe profile in a particularly balanced and complete rendition.

Coffee Name: Finca El Manzano Bourbon Natural El Salvador
Coffee Origin: Santa Ana growing region, El Salvador.
Bottom Line: A very clean, balanced dried-in-the-fruit profile, the only hint of ferment an elegantly restrained dry whisky note.

Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Coffee antiquarians, who may want to sample a very old, traditional strain of Typica, the foundational variety upon which much of the world’s coffee production was originally based, as well those simply interested in a superb Kona cup that is both deeply lush yet suavely brisk.
Those who enjoy the Pacamara pleasure: depth, resonance, low-toned fruit and flowers, sweet with a slight savory edge.
Those who enjoy the richness and depth of a fine Pacamara.

Coffee Name: Panama Gesha Ninety Plus Perci Red
Bottom Line: For those who can afford it, an extraordinary coffee, perfectly structured, intricate and exotic in flavor and aroma.
Briskly authoritative version of the great, aromatic Yirgacheffe cup.
Fine structure and a particularly wide range of aroma/flavor notes both express and exhilaratingly transcend the classic Guatemala cup.
Anyone who loves coffee; spectacularly complex aroma and flavor erupts from a complete, balanced structure.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy complex, resonantly bittersweet beverages. A superbly structured coffee with intricate and surprising aroma/flavor notes, deeper-toned and more pungent than we typically associate with southern Ethiopia coffees.
A superb Sumatra in the newer style: deep, exotic but balanced, dry but juicy.

Coffee Origin: Haraz (also spelled Haraaz) growing region, north-central Yemen
Bottom Line: Unusual profile from a rarely imported origin will interest aficionados and casual coffee drinkers who enjoy sweetly tart fruit character but avoid aggressive acidity.
A fine exemplar of the gently balanced, quietly seductive, Bourbon-influenced style of Guatemala.
Those who enjoy pungently bracing medium-dark-roasted coffees and who want to help improve the difficult lives of small-holding Haitian farmers.
A Yirgacheffe-lover’s Yirgacheffe: briskly sweet, complex, floral, buoyant and exhilarating.
The deep, rich side of the great Kenya profile.
Classicists who want a little more than classic. Superb, balanced structure with a bonus of deeply resonant, engaging aromatics.
A glorious old-fashioned Yirgacheffe: lavishly soaring flowers, bracing citrus, crisp cacao. A coffee to wake one up in every respect.
Exhilarating, intense cup for aficionados who can afford it.

Coffee Name: Elida Estate Natural Typica and Catuai
Bottom Line: Adventurers and those who have no issue with glorious excess.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Sonora Estate Honey Bourbon
Bottom Line: Discreet adventurers. Classically balanced structure, quietly exotic aromatics.
Those who value a wide range of exotic nuance, from particularly fragrant aromatic wood to crisp cacao notes to a deeply spicy floral character.
An unusual profile for aficionados: brisk yet deep, lush yet savory.
Those who enjoy intense but refined acidity and bright, layered complexity.

Coffee Origin: El Quiche Department, south central Guatemala
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy depth and low-toned resonance in a small-producer, Fair-Trade-certified coffee.
The briskly bittersweet, deeply savory character displayed by some Pacamaras is on impressive display here.
Full body and a fresh, aromatic cedar in a round-toned but lively cup.

Coffee Origin: El Quiche Department, south central Guatemala
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a lush, rather exotic fruit and florals cup with a crisp, drying edge. The price represents an excellent value for a distinctive coffee.
Classic Antigua: delicately balanced in acidity and structure and gently saturated with flowers, honey and chocolate.
