Classically deep-toned, pungently chocolaty Huehuetenango for fans of the type and the style.
A fine exemplar of the sweet lucidity of the celebrated Antigua cup.

Delicate yet astounding in its juicy, complex, floral sweetness. Brew this very expensive, very sensitive coffee carefully; in particular, avoid pouring the water too hot if you brew manually; target 200F or so. Should be fine in automatic filter drip machines, which typically brew at relatively low temperatures.
This is a Kenya lovers’ coffee, startling and unique. Also a good place to start for those who are still unclear about the sensory drama associated with the best Kenyas.
A lush but cleanly crisp, balanced dried-in-the-fruit coffee.

Coffee Origin: Boquete growing region, Chiriqui Province, western Panama.
Bottom Line: Those who prefer subtlety and balance to brightness and power.

Coffee Origin: El Naranjo growing region, El Salvador.
Bottom Line: hose who enjoy beverages in which natural sweetness is deepened by a discreet savory pungency.
A naturally sweet, comfortable coffee with an aromatic that shares the freshness of moist, fresh-cut wood with an appealing floral-toned caramel.

Coffee Origin: Ka'u growing district, Big Island of Hawaii
Bottom Line: Classic honey, aromatic fir, flowers and citrus notes on steroids; intense, juicy, complete.
A balanced, softly bright cup in a satisfyingly classic, Kona-associated style.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy rich, complexly lush beverages: ports, for example, or sweet, malty dark beers.
Those who enjoy a roundly tart Central America cup with a classic complement of aromatics.
A unique and precious profile, breezy and meadowy in it floral character, crisply complete.
A combination of honeyish sweetness and crisp, dry mouthfeel should please lovers of complex white table wines.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Aguilera Brothers Finca Le Licho Micro-Lot
Coffee Origin: West Valley growing region, Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Fine balance and superb finish in this summery, briskly sweet classic.

Coffee Name: Colombia Valle del Cauca Cerro Azul Geisha AAA
Coffee Origin: Valle del Cauca growing region, Colombia.
Bottom Line: Amazing coffee; a whole basket of fruit and a field of flowers. If you can handle the price go for it.
Those who enjoy the sweet, acidy brightness of a high-grown, light-roasted cup with an intense, original aromatic bonus.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Wide range of aromatic intrigue in this very complex variation on the Ethiopia dried-in-the-fruit cup.
A hint of spicy aromatic wood deepens and complicates a plush mouthfeel and sweet-toned, chocolaty aroma and flavor.
Those who enjoy briskly dry though full-flavored white wines.
Those who enjoy a balance of almost candyish sweetness and tart citrus in a classic Central America cup.
Those who enjoy a classic cup with fine structure and a quietly complete set of aromatics: a little chocolate, a little citrus, a shimmer of flowers.
Those who enjoy a quietly classic breakfast cup, crisp and resonant.

Coffee Origin: Marcala growing region, La Paz Department, Honduras.
Bottom Line: Gently tart acidity enlivens a suavely classic cup.
Those who enjoy a deep, pungent variation on the classic Central America cup. The Bourbon heritage of the Pacas variety may account for some of the pungent depth of this rather distinctive profile.
Those who enjoy quiet subtlety, soft acidity, and a graceful finish in a classic Central America cup.
Those who enjoy a piney, slightly savory hint complicating a richly sweet, dark-chocolaty cup.

Coffee Origin: San Juan, Naranjo growing region, Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: A superb and subtly exotic variation for those who love the pure, classic Central America cup.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, Big Island of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: The seductive, silky softness of the best Konas boosted by an extraordinary light, shimmering acidity.
An extraordinary Kenya, original and intense yet accessible.
A rich, savory-edged variation on the great Kenya profile.
An original and thoroughly engaging variation on the Ethiopia dried-in-the-fruit or “natural” cup that introduces a crisp, savory-sweet intrigue to the fruit and flowers typical of the type.

Coffee Origin: Tarrazu growing region, central Costa Rica
Bottom Line: Should appeal to coffee classicists who want just a hint of the lushly exotic in their classic Central America cup.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Sonora Estate Natural Bourbon
Bottom Line: A dried-in-the-fruit coffee that impressively balances crisp savory and lush fruit and floral tendencies.

Coffee Origin: San Agustín growing region, Huila Department, southern Colombia
Bottom Line: Those who prefer a smooth, crisply nutty morning cup with hints of a fudgy chocolate and a gently backgrounded acidity.
One of the most quintessentially classic Kenyas we have cupped in a long time. If any coffee merits the term elegant this one does.
Those who enjoy a strong-structured, aromatically complex classic cup.
An outstanding choice for those coffee drinkers who look for a lively and quietly distinctive yet low-acid cup.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Finca El Quizarra White Honey
Bottom Line: Those who prefer subtlety to show.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: A fine, elegant variation on the great southern Ethiopian dried-in-the-fruit cup.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Fine range of sensation in a brisk but juicy cup.
Those who value skillfully light-roasted coffees with richly sweet but uncompromisingly bright acidity supporting a pure and gentle complexity.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Rio Jorco El Llano Honey
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy brisk floral-toned beverages that are delicate yet authoritative.

Coffee Origin: El Cedral, Santa Barbara Department, Honduras.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy dry but complexly aromatic beverages.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: The particular genius of Ethiopia wet-processed coffees from the best mills and growing regions of southern Ethiopia is beautifully on display here: lavish floral sweetness grounded in crisp chocolate, bright, juicy acidity, silky mouthfeel.
Bright acidity and rich floral character in a classic Kenya.

Coffee Origin: Oromia and Yirgacheffe growing regions, Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those likely to enjoy a fine and original variation on the great Ethiopian cup: brightly juicy, deeply complex.

Coffee Origin: Nekempte District, Oromia Region, western Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: The sweet flowers and tart fruit of Ethiopia on steroids; intense and exhilarating cup.

Coffee Origin: Lake Toba or Mandheling growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Admirers of the traditional Sumatra profile will find very little of it here, but they will find a quietly complex and gently balanced cup.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: An attractive balance of drying, slightly savory pungency and chocolaty sweetness in this original variation on the Sumatra cup.

Coffee Origin: Lake Toba growing region, northern Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Moderately dark-roasted and delicately original variation on the Sumatra wet-hulled cup.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: The pungent, berry-toned dark chocolate showed an almost Kenya-like intensity in this complexly original variation on the Sumatra cup.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: The earthy side of elegance in a fine and rather traditional variation on the great wet-hulled Sumatra profile.

Coffee Origin: Aceh growing region, northwestern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: This well-structured variant on the Sumatra profile, with its pungent fruit and big, juicy acidity, should please aficionados of the type.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Spice and butterscotch suggestions in particular distinguish this fine, elegant variation on the great Sumatra wet-hulled cup.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Those likely to enjoy a fine variation on the classic Sumatra structure: simultaneously tart, juicy and richly earthy.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy the classic Sumatra balance between lush fruit and deeper, pungent notes, in this case the moist, spicy earthiness of fresh pipe tobacco.
Splendid example of the extravagantly aromatic Yirgacheffe cup. Will please and excite any way you take it, but should make a particularly fine iced coffee.
Sweetly dry, berry-toned Kenya elegance in a moderately dark-roasted format.
Aficionados interested in an unusual origin (Java village garden coffees) with a quietly but distinctly unusual aromatic, chocolate- and halvah-like.
Those who enjoy the intense, sweetly bright style of the great Kenya cup.
Maragogipe is generally known for its big, showy beans rather than for its cup character, but this Maragogipe defies expectation with a lush and original aromatic profile.
A moderately dark roast develops the rich complexity of the floral notes in this fine rendition of the great Yirgacheffe profile.

Coffee Origin: Tarrazu growing region, central Costa Rica
Bottom Line: Subtle and quietly original. Definitely don’t ruin the delicacy of this gently engaging coffee with whitener.
Those who admire well-structured, balanced profiles in the classic Latin-American mode.
Almost syrupy sweet, juicily tart, with profound and original complexity. An amazing Sumatra.

Coffee Origin: Tarrazu growing region, central Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Classic Costa Rica balance with original, intriguing aromatics.
An unusual coffee, simultaneously sweet and floral with a crisp, underlying cocoaish aromatic wood note that gives the profile authority.
Those who enjoy a rich but delicate cup with quietly original aromatics and excellent social and environmental credentials.

Coffee Name: Mexican El Triunfo Fair Trade Organic
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a fine example of a round, deep, less acidy profile.

Coffee Name: Guatemala Finca La Esperanza Pacamara COE 7
Bottom Line: Those who buy this coffee for the novelty of the very large bean size will be further rewarded by a quietly original aroma/flavor complex: the butter and nut suggestions are complicated by juicy citrus and lush flowers.
Classic in structure yet subtly surprising and original in its aromatics, this coffee should please classicists and explorers alike.

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: A classically intense floral-and-citrus washed Ethiopia coffee that will please lovers of the type and perhaps attract some converts as well.

Coffee Origin: Apaneca Municipality, Ahuachapan Department, El Salvador.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy subtly unusual aromatics and silky balance.
Those who prefer a deep, round, resonantly pungent cup with considerable complexity and backgrounded but vibrant acidity.
A very ripe, elegant acidity leads in this quietly classic Kenya.
Yirgacheffe is already one of the world’s most explosively complex coffees; this is a Yirgacheffe on steroids, huge and astounding in its aromatic impact.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: An exceptional and unusual dried-in-the-fruit coffee, with the sweetness and aromatic complexity characteristic of the type expressed cleanly without the distraction of over-the-top fruit. Not your typical Sumatra, by the way; closer in character to certain of the finest dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopias.
A balanced, comfortable coffee with a plush mouthfeel and flavor notes ranging from pungently crisp to lushly sweet.

Coffee Origin: Caranavi Province, La Paz Department, Bolivia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy depth, resonance and a juicy rather than bright acidity.
Those who prefer quietly resonant, gently complex coffees.
Those who enjoy crisp, slightly earthy and savory beverages.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Don Jose Micro Lot
Coffee Origin: West Valley growing region, Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: A quiet, comfortable coffee in the best sense; lively yet balanced, gentle yet engaging.
Quietly original in its graceful integration of savory depth and floral sweetness.

Coffee Origin: Jiwaka Province, western highlands of Papua New Guinea.
Bottom Line: Finely balanced, classically complete cup should satisfy almost any coffee drinker.
Those who enjoy variations on the gently fermented, natural or dried-in-the-fruit cup. This version is drier and more rye-whisky-toned than most, which tend to be sweeter and more brandy-like.
Those who enjoy a briskly savory-edged breakfast cup.
Classic Mexico: clean, softly bright, quietly complex, with a hint of the elegant dry berry note associated with the heirloom Bourbon variety.

Coffee Origin: Canton Illimani, Caranavi Province, west-central Bolivia.
Bottom Line: A classic Bolivia cup: lovely structure with gentle but vibrant acidity; quietly complex aromatics.
Those who enjoy depth and savory complexity in a brewed coffee.
An unusual opportunity for decaf drinkers to enjoy the sweetly tart, grapefruity character of a fine Papua New Guinea coffee offered as a single-origin.
Those who enjoy a balanced, chocolate-toned darker roasted cup.
Those who enjoy purity and delicacy in a crisply refreshing morning cup.

Coffee Origin: Nekempte District, Oromia Region, western Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: This striking but accessible coffee should please anyone, while aficionados of the great Ethiopia wet-processed profile will find its wide range of aromatics familiar yet arrestingly original.
Quintessential Kenya, alive with characteristic Kenya berry notes lushly sweet yet crisply dry and animated by a ripe and accessible acidity.
Offers everything: Seething, opulent flavor atop a firm, classic structure.
Those who value sweetness without sentimentality.

Coffee Origin: Caranavi Province, La Paz Department, Bolivia.
Bottom Line: A complete and classic Latin-American-style cup, with big body, bright but balanced acidity, and a lush and juicy set of flavor and aroma notes.

Coffee Origin: Eastern Highlands Province, Papua New Guinea
Bottom Line: Anyone who enjoys purity without simplicity. Lively, balanced and classic.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, "Big Island" of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Nicely expresses the characteristic soft acidity, sweetness and delicate complexity of the finest Kona coffees.

Coffee Name: Bolivia Caarnavi Buenavista Organic Light Roast
Coffee Origin: Caranavi Province, La Paz Department, Bolivia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a lighter roasted, delicately brisk, cleanly honey-toned cup.
In many respects a classic Peru: soft, buoyant, balanced.

Coffee Origin: Carnavi Province, La Paz Department, Bolivia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy delicacy and comfort in a genial medium-roasted cup.

Those who enjoy naturally crisp, pleasingly bittersweet sensations. This definitely is not the bittersweetness of darker roasted coffees, for example, but is a very graceful bittersweet tartness reminiscent of certain fruits and berries.

Coffee Origin: Caranavi Province, La Paz Department, Bolivia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a delicately crisp citrus enveloped in honey, floral and cocoa-toned sweetness.
Those who enjoy pungently sweet, complex beverages with a wide range of sensation, from citrusy tart to floral-toned sweet.

Coffee Origin: Carnavi Province, La Paz Department, Bolivia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy beverages that combine savory depth with complex sweetness.
Those who enjoy a classically structured morning cup: bright, big-bodied, but balanced.

Coffee Name: Ecuador El Batan Fair Trade Organic
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a very pure, balanced lighter-roasted cup, graceful and lyric.

Coffee Name: 100 Percent Puna Kazumura Reserve Peaberry Medium Dark
Bottom Line: This would be a striking and unusual coffee from anywhere in the world, but it is a particular surprise coming from Hawaii, where sweetness and balance are the positive norm rather than the startling aromatic originality of this Puna peaberry.
A crisp, roast-influenced version of the great Gesha profile, with its lush flowers and brisk chocolate.

Coffee Name: Guatemala El Injerto Pandora Del Carmen Pacamara
Bottom Line: The particular sensory genius of the Pacamara variety is exhibited well here: savory-sweet depth, crisp cedary chocolate, floral top notes and a slightly bitterish, brightly zesty citrus. The classic crossed with the exotic.
Those who enjoy purity, elegance and delicate complexity in a lighter-roasted cup.
Tart and savory tendencies balance great sweetness in a structure that supports an intriguingly complex set of aromas and flavors.
Those who enjoy a coffee that is easy-drinking and accessible yet still offers aromatic intrigue.

Coffee Origin: Volcan de Santa Ana regioin, El Salvador.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy complex expressions of richly and sweetly tart sensations in juices and cuisine.
A fine exemplar of the great Yirgacheffe cup, juicy, bright and dramatically aromatic.
Those who enjoy Central African tart berry and floral chocolate character in a briskly bright but balanced cup.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Sidama Province, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: A massive, robust example of the fruity, brandyish style of Ethiopian dried-in-the-fruit coffee, with a savory weight in cup and finish complicating the usual big, blueberryish sweetness. Those coffee drinkers who know and value Ethiopian dried-in-the-fruit coffee should enjoy this hearty variant.

Coffee Origin: Valle del Cauca growing region, Colombia.
Bottom Line: Those who prefer a crisp but deep-toned and caramelly breakfast cup.
Lovers of the more refined style of Sumatras may find this coffee interesting and appealing, as will those who enjoy beverages that combine great natural sweetness with a crisp, dry mouthfeel.
In particular, those who enjoy the grand style of Kenya, big, juicy, bright, crisp, but anyone who wants a fine breakfast cup as arresting as it is balanced.

Coffee Origin: Gera District of Oromia Region, western Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who value intensity and excitement in flavor and sweet-toned, juicy acidity.

Coffee Origin: San Agustín growing region, Huila Department, southwestern Colombia.
Bottom Line: Those who value pure, delicately classic breakfast coffees. Don’t even think about putting whitener in this one.

Nice balance of lush, slightly fermenty fruit and floral sweetness with a gently drying briskness should please those who enjoy such juxtapositions in ales and whiskies, for example, or good port wines.
Those who prefer a round, quietly complex cup, comfortable with a hint of the exotic.

Usually the rare Maragogipe wows us with its giant beans but disappoints in the cup. This lot, however, displays an interesting and impressive sensory profile, making it an appealing buy both for the coffee curious and those simply interested in a satisfying and unusual cup.
The style of coffee we used to call “after-dinner,” though its resonant richness, quiet complexity and roast-moderated acidity should please any time of day.

Coffee Name: Harfusa Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Fair Trade Organic
Bottom Line: Smoothly tart and lushly sweet, surprisingly full in mouthfeel, deeply nuanced in aroma and flavor, this is a morning cup that both expresses and transcends classic.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: A light but fully developed roast encourages expression of a massive and ultimately harmonious complexity that should surprise and please any coffee drinker save the most conventional in taste.
Lovers of very pure, delicately balanced beverages.
Those who enjoy a crisply sweet, suavely nuanced breakfast cup.
Those who enjoy a classic, straightforward breakfast cup, sweetly bright but not sharp.

Coffee Name: Cosecha de Oro Colombia Light Roast
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy gentle medium-roasted blends with soft acidity and quiet, layered flavor and aromatics.
Decaf drinkers will find some pleasures here, including smooth, pleasing mouthfeel and a nut-toned, caramelly sweetness.
The cushiony, plush acidity and floral sweetness makes this an accessible and inviting version of the great Kenya profile.
Classic Kenya richly displays all the pleasures of the type: big but rounded acidity; elegantly complex, sweetly tart berry notes; silky mouthfeel.

Coffee Origin: Karatina district, Nyeri growing region, Kenya.
Bottom Line: Anyone who enjoys a briskly sweet morning cup; the particularly complex floral notes range from bitter and hoppy to lushly honeyish.
One of the best luwaked coffees we have sampled over the past few years, with genuinely unique aromatics. Only you can decide whether those unique aromatics are worth the high price.

Coffee Name: Honduras Santa Barbara Beneficio San Vicente Caracalillo
Bottom Line: Tart, dry berry juxtaposed with floral sweetness makes this an attractive variation for those who enjoy the great SL28 Kenya profiles.

Coffee Name: Honduras Santa Barbara Finca Las Brisas
Bottom Line: A quietly complex, classically balanced breakfast cup.
Those who enjoy sweetness without sentimentality.
Those who value skillfully light-roasted coffees of great purity that preserve a meadow-like freshness and brisk sweetness.

A very pure, crisp, light-roasted example of the normally more lushly fruit-and-brandy-toned dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia profile. Think honeyish flowers and citrus rather than dark chocolate and blueberries.
Those who prefer the deep and vibrant to the bright and showy.
Unusual opportunity to taste a good Haitian coffee, with the chocolate and soft, rounded acidity long associated with this perennially troubled origin.

Coffee Origin: El Quiche Department, south central Guatemala
Bottom Line: Quietly exotic flavor and balanced structure in a light-roast presentation provides a satisfying variation on the Central America cup.
Those who enjoy a brightly acidy yet sweetly nuanced cup.

Coffee Origin: Kersa district, Oromia region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who already know they enjoy the slightly fermented, fruit-toned Ethiopia dried-in-the-fruit profile will enjoy this clean, elegant rendition of the type. For those who have never experimented with the style, an excellent starting point.

Coffee Name: Ecuador La Bendicion de Dios & El Nogel
Bottom Line: Superbly refined Latin American style breakfast cup should please any drinker of light- to medium-roasted coffees. The sweetly tart citrus and crisp cocoa give just enough grounding authority to the soft, enveloping floral character.
Lovers of dry but gently fragrant white table wines.
Those who enjoy beverages that combine great sweetness with dry authority; certain floral but minerally white wines for example.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Lovers of the great traditional Sumatra profile should enjoy this lively, elegantly complex version of the style.
Superb, balanced but intensely aromatic example of the great Yirgacheffe profile.

Coffee Name: Mexico Santa Teresa BCS 02: Cabernet Franc Barrel
Bottom Line: Should make a superb dessert coffee, while aficionados of high-end coffee innovation will find it interesting, perhaps remarkable.
Distinctive aromatics and an essential balance and sweetness should make this an attractive, exciting breakfast cup for almost any one.

Coffee Origin: Nyeri growing region, Central Highlands, Kenya.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy the richly bright, juicy side of the great Kenya cup.
Fine version of the great Yirgacheffe profile, with an emphasis on delicate sweetness and brisk, complex flowers.
Those who enjoy the moist foresty notes of Sumatra Arabica coffees may enjoy this understated variant on the style.
Those who enjoy pungent, rough beverages like retsina wines and mescals.
Sensory adventurers interested in sampling a decent quality dried-in-the-fruit Robusta.

Aficionado adventurers curious about this very unusual blend of coffee species, although the impact of dry-processing (drying in the fruit) and a darkish roast may obscure any clear view of the sensory impact of species.

This is a coffee for aficionados curious about this very rare blend of coffee species, although the impact of dry-processing (drying in the fruit) and a darkish roast may obscure any clear view of the sensory impact of species.
Complex, pleasing variation on the chocolate-and-brandy dried-in-the-fruit Yirgacheffe profile and an excellent value.

Coffee Origin: Gomma Woreda, Limu region, southwestern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy the honeyish, crisply sweet, meadowy character of a very pure washed coffee at a relatively light roast.
Those who enjoy a discreetly roast-muted version of the floral- and fruit-toned Ethiopia profile at a very attractive price.
A brilliant example of the original Gesha profile, for those who can afford it.
Those who enjoy a natural, honeyish sweetness and jammy fruit in a very clean dried-in-the-fruit profile.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: A floral-toned, slightly savory version of the great chocolate-and-brandy southern Ethiopia dried-in-the-fruit profile.
The play of sweetness – honey, blueberry – against crisper notes – roasted cocoa nib, herb – gives this dried-in-the-fruit profile its particular distinction.
Sweet and floral but delicately dry, should please lovers of Rieslings and similar styles of white table wine.
A soothing but engaging holiday blend that should make a small contribution to peace, on earth and at the dinner table.

Classically please-em-all holiday blend, though aficionados might find this updated version of the ancient Mocha-Java blend interesting for its blend composition. The Java, as it does in the original blend archetype, contributes a rounding base; in this case supporting a gently bright, crisply berry-toned Kenya.
A versatile, drinkable holiday blend with attractive social and environmental credentials at a very attractive price.
Subtle authority and gentle sweetness; excellent holiday value.

Coffee Origin: San Agustín growing region, Huila Department, southern Colombia
Bottom Line: A pure, deep-toned, full-bodied cup in the classic Colombia style. Produced from trees of the Caturra variety, a selection of Bourbon that is usually rather basic in the cup, but that here displays some of the celebrated pungent berry character of its parent.
Not a holiday blend, but a felicitous choice of single-origin coffee that expresses an appropriately winter holiday sensory theme of fruit, chocolate and pleasingly pungent aromatic wood.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Superb version of the Ethiopian dried-in-the-fruit or “natural” profile, with the complex, juicy sweetness of the type expressed with unusual purity and vivacity.

Certainly the sweetest, and probably the best, Rwanda we have sampled for some time. The sweetness is the natural kind, a deeply nuanced expression of orchard-like purity enriched by a tactfully caramelizing roast. You certainly don’t need sweetener for this one.
Great depth, range and balance of sensation make this an exceptional choice for any season, any holiday.

As refreshing and heady as a tropical morning, a cliché that seems absolutely justified by this light, levitating version of the rare Gesha variety. Buy it close to when you’re going to drink it, and if you give it, make sure it doesn’t sit in the gift pile too long.
Simply a superb, complete coffee; the great Kenya style at its finest.

A light but fully developed roast foregrounds an extraordinary version of a very rare coffee. If you splurge on it for the holidays do your splurging close to when you are planning to drink the coffee, brew it carefully, and leave the sweetener on the counter and the dairy in the fridge.
Anyone who can afford it. An amazing coffee.

Coffee Name: Guatemala El Injerto Pandora Del Carmen Pacamara
Bottom Line: Aficionados interested in enjoying the deep, low-toned, savory fruit tendencies of the Pacamara variety.

Those who understand and appreciate a classically bright coffee. There is nothing sour, bitter or astringent here; instead a lushly sweet-toned, flavor-nuanced tart sensation vibrates at the heart of the profile.

Coffee Origin: Wahgi Valley, Western Highlands, Papua New Guinea.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy the quietly exotic.
An aficionado’s dried-in-the-fruit coffee with the brandy-like appeal of the type complicated by hints of clove and sandalwood.

Coffee Name: Colombia La Esperanza Cerro Azul Geisha
Bottom Line: I can’t call a coffee this expensive a bargain, but it is less expensive than the more celebrated Panama Geshas, and given its extraordinary complexity and character, an excellent value for those who appreciate and can afford the genuinely exceptional.

Coffee Origin: Valle del Cauca growing region, Colombia.
Bottom Line: A balanced, elegant version of the extravagantly aromatic Gesha profile.
The crisply sweet berry character of great Kenyas shows up here in this very distinctive, resonantly elegant profile.
Deep, whisky-and-honey aromatic character may make this cup a particularly good afternoon or evening choice.
Delicately complex, sweet, very slightly savory, a subtly unusual profile for subtle palates.
Classic Guatemalan variation on the classic American breakfast cup: sweetly acidy, big-bodied, complex, rich.
A brisk, rather elegant bittersweet character makes this an unusual variation on the great Yirgacheffe profile.
Giddily sweet and complex expression of the Gesha cup. If you can afford it, try it.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: A superb, unapologetic Sumatra of the deep, cleanly and richly earthy style.
Classic Central American breakfast cup: balanced, juicy, complete.
Those who prefer red wines and whisky to white wines and vodka.

Coffee Origin: La Paz District, Marcala growing region, Honduras.
Bottom Line: Lovers of crisply complex, dry white table wines.
Very low price; very, very poor quality by any standard that we know of.
We’ve tasted this brand and this coffee when it was considerably better. Maybe you’ll get lucky with yours.
Nothing wrong; nothing much right here either except for the very attractive price. A clean but very simple, woody cup.
Those looking for Starbucks’ version of “mellow and soft” (very) at an attractive price.
Those who enjoy a cleanly delicate medium roast at a reasonable price.
A cigar-and-leather-armchair style coffee, deep and richly brandy-like.
Classic Kenya: intense, elegant, complex.

Unusual coffee, perhaps more distinguished than our rating suggests. Those who value dry, savory undercurrents in beverages – in aged tequilas and cachaças, to give just two examples – should particularly enjoy this coffee.

The celebrated Kenya dry berry character, aka “black currant,” for us displayed here as sweetly tangy, juicy guava. Everything works in this superbly complete, graceful coffee, simultaneously simple and complex, altogether classic.
Those who find typical Yirgacheffes too light-bodied and floral may particularly enjoy this variant on the type, with its fuller mouthfeel and emphasis on lemon and deeper fig-molasses notes.

Coffee Name: Organic Costa Rica Helsar Finca Santa Lucia
Bottom Line: Delicate, lively, silky cup should please palates tuned to subtlety.
A balanced, quietly complex cup with thorough-going socially and environmentally progressive credentials.
Aficionados or anyone interested in a particularly deep, pungently lush variation on the classic Kenya cup.

Coffee Origin: Kefa (Kaffa) Province, Oromia region, southwestern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Sweet, intense Ethiopia with classic citrus and flowers.
A characteristically suave and quietly balanced coffee from the celebrated Antigua valley.
Fine variant on the great Kenya profile: Vivacious, sweetly bright, juicy.
Persuasive local cause, nicely balanced cup.

Coffee Name: Dominican Republic Cafe Femenino Organic Fair Trade
Bottom Line: Crisp, delicate cup offers impressive support for low-income women both in the Dominican Republic through the Café Femenino program and to local women in crisis in Columbus, Ohio.
Unusual cup with quietly distinctive aroma and flavor contributing to an important cause.
A rather rough-edged but vigorous, engaging blend supporting a timely cause with personal resonance at Caribou.
Gently lively cup for backyard birders and anyone who prefers mellow to bright.
Those who enjoy a roundly pungent cup with relatively low acidity and who admire the uncompromisingly hands-on approach of this community-based roaster.
Those who enjoy a gentle, roundly brisk cup offered by an idealistic branch of a six-generation Brazilian farming family.
Those who enjoy exhilarating aromatics, a briskly tart structure and grassroots soccer.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: An unusual dried-in-the-fruit profile, honeyish but pungent and deep. Nice any time, but should make an exceptional late-in-the-day cup.
Aficionados interested in sampling one of the most original and striking dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopian coffees to appear this year.
A fine variation on the classic washed Yirgacheffe profile, with exhilarating lime and lush floral notes.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia Region, Sidama Province, Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy the extravagant intensity of southern Ethiopia dried-in-the-fruit coffees.
An opportunity to taste the spectacular Gesha profile at peak complexity and nuance. Reasonably priced for an Esmeralda Gesha.

Coffee Origin: Canas Verdes, Boquete growing region, western Panama.
Bottom Line: Super aficionados on a budget. A (believe it or not) reasonably priced version of the extravagantly distinctive and rare Esmeralda Gesha.
An adventurer’s coffee, deeply and idiosyncratically complex with aromatic surprises from aroma through finish.
Aficionados interested in a very cleanly and originally expressed version of the Ethiopia natural cup; anyone who enjoys exotic but balanced complexity.
Those who enjoy sensory excitement and surprise.
Those who can handle both intensity and complexity in a striking and unusual coffee.
A contemplative sort of coffee, deep, quiet, sweet without sentiment.
Those who enjoy deep, authoritative, richly stated coffees with a hint of roasty pungency.
Those who can afford a finely executed dried-in-the-fruit version of the great Gesha profile.
An easy-going Kenya, with the sweetly tart berry character of fine Kenyas but without their often challengingly bright acidity.

Coffee Origin: Volcan de Santa Ana regioin, El Salvador.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy subtle, gentle beverages.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica La Candelilla Honey Peaberry
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy white wines that are delicate and crisply dry yet sweet.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica El Espino Yellow Honey Caturra
Coffee Origin: Zarcero Canton, Alajuela Province, Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy subtly sweet breakfast coffees with understated acidity.

The honey process deepens and rounds the characteristically tart Bourbon fruit, making this a good choice for aficionados exploring a variation on the great Bourbon profile, and for anyone who prefers rich pungency to bright acidity.

Coffee Origin: Mozonte district, Nuevo Segovia Department, Nicaragua.
Bottom Line: Aficionados interested in a coffee with a subtly unusual profile, a little Sumatra-like, a little natural-Brazil-like, but ultimately unique in its damply woodsy and nut-toned character.
A subtle coffee subtly light-roasted produces a crisply delicate, refreshing cup.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Herbazu Villa Sarchi Honey
Coffee Origin: West Valley growing region, Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Honey character in a honey coffee; a walk in the woods in the springtime.
Coffee iconoclasts. Complex and unexpected.

Coffee Name: El Salvador La Roxanita Pulped Natural
Bottom Line: Very sweet, quite tart; those who don’t normally care for tartly acidy coffees may be persuaded by this deep, richly subtle rendition.

Coffee Origin: Apaneca district, Ahuachapan Department, El Salvador.
Bottom Line: Lovers of fruity, lightly fermented dried-in-the-fruit “natural” coffees should particularly enjoy this coffee, which treads the same sensory track as fruity naturals but with a bit more subtlety.
A quiet but delicately complex morning cup.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Impressively rich and complexly chocolate-toned variation on the dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia cup.
A quiet but distinctive Yirgacheffe that should please those who like their flowers, citrus and cocoa in balance, present but not insistent.
Sweet but crisp variant on the great Kenya profile.
Exhilaratingly exotic yet accessible, a coffee that should please both casual coffee drinkers and aficionados. Absolutely do not ruin this coffee with sweetener; should be very nice iced.

Coffee Origin: Lake Tawar basin, Aceh Province, northern Indonesia, Indonesia
Bottom Line: Lovers both of the old, funky Sumatras as well as the new, more refined (yet still intense) versions like this one.

Coffee Origin: El Salto, Boquete growing region, Panama.
Bottom Line: The complex floral notes, which include spicy florals like aromatic tea rose and bitterish florals like lavender, are one good reason for aficionados to seek out this unusual coffee.
A gently crisp, floral, refreshing version of the great Kenya profile.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy the extravagant and uncompromising.
Those who enjoy a bracingly bright old-fashioned American cup.
Aficionados and coffee adventurers may enjoy this unusual dried-in-the-fruit profile, in which distinct floral notes are supported by backgrounded, savory, earth-toned suggestions.
Those who enjoy heavily hopped ales and other pleasingly bitter-edged beverages.

Coffee Name: Panama Hacienda La Esmeralda Geisha Baru
Coffee Origin: Cañas Verdes, Boquete growing region, western Panama.
Bottom Line: Honeyish, meadowy version of the great Gesha profile.
More chocolaty depth and richness than brandy and fruit in this surprisingly clean and balanced dried-in-the-fruit natural.
Any coffee drinker with the cash to buy an amazing expression of sensory complexity.

Coffee Name: Esmeralda Leon, Panama Geisha Auction Lot
Coffee Origin: Cañas Verdes, Boquete growing region, western Panama.
Bottom Line: Those who can handle the price and the intensity: a Gesha on steroids.

Coffee Origin: Kersa district, Oromia region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: A splendid dried-in-the-fruit-style Ethiopia coffee, richly complex with the classic blueberry note often associated with the type.

An admirably, indeed strikingly, unorthodox coffee from a major coffee company. If you are certain you only like pure, sweetly bright, classically clean high-grown coffees don’t bother with this one, but the open-minded should sample this deep, savory-sweet, whiskyish effort.
An understated, nicely structured breakfast cup for those who prefer the calm to the dramatic.
A woodsy kind of coffee, with its appealing roasted cocoa nib, cedar and honey suggestions.
Aficionados should enjoy the remarkable tropical turn the tart, complex Kenya fruit takes here.
Those who enjoy lighter roasted coffees; in this case the lightish roast promotes the coffee’s rose-like floral character and a crisply lively acidity.
A breakfast cup both exotic in its aromatics and classic in its brisk, suavely balanced acidity.
Those who enjoy lighter-roasted coffees with delicately brisk acidity and fresh, meadowy aromatics.
A darker roast turns the pungent Kenya fruit toward molasses and chocolate and deepens the flowers toward rose. A good Kenya for those who prefer depth to brightness.
Unusual profile for coffee adventurers: Complex, very wide-ranging aromatics with an underlying savory depth to the sweetness.

Coffee lovers interested in sampling a distinctive version of an important historical coffee type. Botanical variety is not specified, but this sample tasted to us as though it brought some heirloom East Africa Bourbon or SL28 character to the cup.
Brisk, refreshing Yirgacheffe. The characteristic Yirgacheffe flowers are not heavy or jasmine-like, but breezy, spring-like and fresh.
A Sumatra taken through finishing school: elegant, poised, but with all of the fruit and forest intrigue intact.
Those who enjoy the contrast and excitement of rich, strongly stated acidity enveloped in great natural sweetness complicated by distinctive aromatics.

Coffee Origin: Kaanapali district, near Lahaina, West Maui, Hawaii
Bottom Line: Aficionados interested in sampling a particularly pure version of the famous Mocca profile. Anyone willing to pay more for an exciting, original yet elegantly balanced coffee.

An opportunity to enjoy a fine Central Africa coffee with classic Bourbon-influenced crisp juiciness while supporting some of the many women who struggle to raise their families on very modest returns from small coffee farms.
Particularly brisk and complex version of the great Yirgacheffe profile.

Coffee Name: Wata Dara Ethiopian Sidamo Fair Trade Organic
Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Intense, dramatic, but refreshingly juicy Ethiopia for those who enjoy excitement at breakfast.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Tarrazu Microlot El Liano
Bottom Line: The citrus and softly sweet chocolate suggestions animate a pleasing, drinkable morning cup.
Gently bright and subtly nuanced breakfast cup in a rare Smithsonian Bird-Friendly-certified coffee.
Balanced, well-structured breakfast blend with simple but attractive aromatics and a pleasing dark chocolate nuance.

Coffee Name: 100 Percent Kona Coffee Extra Fancy Medium Roast
Coffee Origin: Kona growing district, "Big Island" of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Balanced, medium-dark-roasted Kona with the chocolate and easy comfort associated with this famous origin.
Happy fence-sitters. Nicely situated on the cusp between medium- and moderately dark-roasted, with an easy-drinking caramel and plum character.
Refined floral and deep fruit sweetness makes this an original and engaging variation on the great Kenya cup.
Complexly structured Kenya, sweet yet dry with savory hints. Should please those who enjoy drier, lighter bodied red table wines that keep the fruit in balance.
A deep, syrupy, complex cup suggests desserts and late, leisurely mornings.

Coffee Origin: Caranavi growing region, La Paz Department, Bolivia.
Bottom Line: The sweet floral and crisply cocoa-like aromatics are a good reason to try this quietly distinctive Bolivia.
Those who enjoy dry but floral/spicy white table wines may particularly enjoy this delicately complex coffee.
Those who enjoy cleanly delicate, sweet-toned beverages.
Comfortable coffee: Brisk but not bright, pleasantly full in mouthfeel.
Those who enjoy fruity/oaky red table wines and dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia coffees.
Gentle acidity and briskly complex aromatics should please those who enjoy fine black teas and lighter bodied, spicy red table wines.
Should please those who enjoy delicately dry, complexly floral white table wines.
Gently dry in the mouthfeel yet sweet and berryish in flavor, this coffee defines an admired style of Bourbon cup from Central Africa.
Aficionados and others interested in the intriguingly complex floral character with its spicy/savory underpinning.
Those who enjoy a bright, pure but complex morning cup.
Pure and meadowy but richly authoritative. Sweetness and flowers without sentimentality.
Brightly acidy but sweetly inviting, vibrantly complex Kenya.
Superb balance of lush sweetness, crisply dry mouthfeel and dynamically complex aromatics should please both coffee classicist and romantic.
Balanced, delicate, comfortable, though with gentle aromatic surprises.
The beloved Sumatra earth and fruit character at its purest and most intense.

Coffee Origin: Holualoa (North Kona District), Big Island of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: A very fine Kona in the classic pure, sweet-toned style, a style that is increasingly hard to find in Kona owing to careless fruit removal and drying and tactless dark roasting.
Balanced, naturally sweet, quietly but lushly complex.
Lovers of the idiosyncratic. Those who enjoy Islay single-malt whiskies, lapsang souchong teas, heavy beverages that shock and surprise.
Unusual Kenya profile, deep and savory sweet with layered complexity. Suggests pairing with desserts.

Coffee Name: Laura’s Blend: 100 Percent Kona Coffee Fancy
Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Simply a perfect expression of the sweet, balanced, quietly complete Kona cup.
Delicate but genuinely exotic profile. Blends of dramatically darker and lighter roasted coffees are hard to pull off; this one succeeds.
Lovers of good port wines.
The sort of crisp yet luxurious coffee that used to be tagged for “after dinner,” but I’d say drink it anytime.

Coffee Name: Ethiopian Sidamo Shanta Golba Natural Processed
Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those who favor fruit-forward red wines with lots of oak may be particularly well-suited candidates for this engaging, rather muscular and complex version of the Ethiopia dried-in-the-fruit cup, one that comes with reassuring environmental and social credentials.

Coffee Origin: Carmo de Minas growing region, Brazil, Brazil
Bottom Line: Balanced, delicate breakfast cup with light body but refined finish.

Coffee Origin: Campos Altos growing district, Brazil, Brazil.
Bottom Line: Those who prefer a mild roasty pungency in a chocolate-and-walnut-toned Brazil.

Coffee Origin: Chapada Diamantina growing region, Bahia State, Brazil.
Bottom Line: A lightish roast and clean wet processing encourages a fresh, molasses-like sweetness and gently lively acidity.

Roaster Location: Salt Spring Island, British Colombia, Canada
Coffee Origin: Chapada Diamantina growing region, Bahia State, Brazil.
Bottom Line: Those looking for a juicy, honey-toned morning cup.

Coffee Origin: Sul de Minas growing region, southern Brazil, Brazil.
Bottom Line: A classic Brazil, syrupy, balanced, chocolaty.

Coffee Name: Brazil Fazenda Chapadao de Ferro Peaberry
Bottom Line: Acidity is functional but gentle and backgrounded while dark chocolate and nut notes dominate, making this a complex but comfortable coffee for those who find coffees from East Africa or Central America too forceful or bright.

Coffee Name: Sol do Paraguassu Farm Natural Processed Brazil
Coffee Origin: Chapada Diamantina growing region, Bahia State, Brazil.
Bottom Line: Balanced, gentle, refreshing Brazil, quietly exceptional.
Extraordinary coffee, superlative in all the classic ways.
Complete coffee in the classic Colombia mode.

Coffee Origin: Valle del Cauca growing region, Colombia.
Bottom Line: Big, complete and balanced, a classic Colombia.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Elegantly complex, refined version of the earth and pungent fruit sensations beloved of generations of Sumatra drinkers.
Quietly exotic variation on the Bourbon-influenced Burundi cup: pungently sweet, aromatic wood saturated in vanilla and flowers.
Big but balanced, sweetly complex classic Latin-American breakfast cup.
A fine, balanced, gently crisp cup of the style associated with the best Guatemalas.

Coffee Name: Rwanda Gatare Cup of Excellence Lot 6
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy dry, floral-toned white wines and the pungent dry-berry elegance of fine Kenya coffees.
Non-gardening Sumatra drinkers. A still pungent but rather bright version of the classic Sumatra profile, with only a discreet hint of the usual musty earth.
Those who enjoy big, dry white table wines with complex aromatics. This is an aficionado’s Kenya, elegant but uncompromising in its intense acidity and crisp, pungent fruit.
An aficionado’s Kenya: complexly assertive acidity; rich, dry aromatics and flavor.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Finca Suiza Santa Ana
Coffee Origin: Santa Ana growing region, El Salvador.
Bottom Line: A syrupy body and tart yet ripe fruit notes should please those who indulge in ports and other dessert wines.
Those who enjoy tart, savory sensations like Meyer lemon or tomato-based juices.
Those who think they may enjoy the distinctively dry, slightly savory cocoa, lemony sensation that dominates in this Colombia.
Drinkers of heavily hopped floral ales and dry, aromatic white wines.

Coffee Name: Colombia Las Mercedes 2011 Cup of Excellence #2 Auction Lot
Bottom Line: Lovers of very dry, light-bodied beverages: gins, minerally white table wines.
Lovers of big, resonantly rich Colombias in the classic style.
Both strong-structured and aromatically subtle, with juicy hints of East Africa.
Those who enjoy a balanced but assertively bright breakfast cup.
Classically balanced, delicately complex morning cup. Take it black.

Coffee Origin: Pitalito growing region, Huila Department, Colombia.
Bottom Line: Those who take their coffee black and enjoy a delicate, naturally sweet-toned, cleanly aromatic cup.

Coffee Name: Colombia Huila Monserrate Yaneth Gil Microlot
Bottom Line: Breakfast classicists. This is a complete Colombia coffee, the kind I recall we used to get more often, balanced and flawless in virtually every respect.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing district, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Smoothly bright, pungently refreshing example of the finest traditional style of Sumatra coffee.
Rich, roundly fruit-toned cup should particularly please those who enjoy fine traditional dessert wines.
Lovers of Sumatras and other earthy/fruity coffees. This is a romance coffee: exotic, challenging, exhilarating in its richly stated imperfections.
Lovers of a sweetly crisp, quietly aromatic morning cup.
Fine variation on the floral and citrus East Africa profile: crisp and refreshing morning cup.
The versatility of this quietly complex moderate dark roast should please both black and with whitener.
Delicate yet deeply resonant version of the great classic Yirgacheffe cup.
A Fair Trade and organic presentation of the classic darker roasted Sumatra cup, gently earthy, roasty and chocolate-toned.
A powerfully acidy yet sweetly elegant version of the classic Kenya profile.

Coffee Origin: Santa Rita growing region, El Salvador.
Bottom Line: Aficionados should admire the striking originality of this natural-processed profile with its complex anthology of savory-sweet fruit sensation.

Coffee Name: Mexico Chiapas El Triunfo Biosphere Fair Trade Organic
Bottom Line: Natural sweetness and an exquisitely delicate acidity make this coffee particularly appealing black; even habitual milk pourers should keep their hands off the white stuff with this graceful, crisp cup. Drink it hot; flavor tends to tail off as it cools.

The acidity here is not an intense, brightly lemony sensation, but rather ripe, juicy, and complicated by a cedary, slightly earthy character. Lovers of minerally, complex, only moderately dry white table wines might be particular candidates for this coffee.

A graceful version of the often rough and earthy Sumatra profile. The elements are all here: the moist earthy notes, aromatic wood, malty dark chocolate, butterscotch-like pungency, but in impressive, understated balance.

A potentially delicate, balanced breakfast cup that suffered in our sample from some aromatic fading. For supermarket shoppers a plausible all-Arabica alternative to the dismal, Robusta-based canned options.
Medium-roast drinkers who find themselves out of coffee and close to a Starbucks.
Those who find directness and simplicity a virtue.

This perhaps half-hearted rendition of a traditional medium roast may be aimed at Dunkin’ Donuts drinkers. It seems far too muted for those who enjoy the more assertive acidity and complex aromatics of coffees from the newer, trendier medium-roasters.
A forceful, deep-structured cup, especially when hot.
Those who prefer a robust, muscular richness to balance.
A versatile cup with quiet, balanced authority.
Lovers of fresh, aromatically arresting breakfast coffees.
Those who enjoy fine white table wines that balance mineral and fruit. An impressive Kenya in the slightly austere, elegant dry berry style.
An unusual brisk natural Ethiopia. Aficionados interested in variants on the great Ethiopia cup may particular enjoy it.
The explosive aromatics combined with the sweet-salt-savory structure may appeal to lovers of tequilas and some single malt whiskies.
Energetic and arresting cup. The unusual savory sweet complexity may reflect the heirloom Bourbon cultivar, which is widely grown in Burundi.
Coffee romantics. Exotic aroma and flavor notes make this coffee more African than Colombian.
Low acidity, but given this sample’s badly tainted green coffees, not recommended even for acidity-avoiders.
Genuinely low in acidity, both perceived and measured, but very low in flavor as well.

All of the Hevla samples in our 2012 low-acid cupping displayed green coffee taints, though the acidity, as advertised, was low, based both on a sensory reading of the cup and the pH of the finished beverage.
Not recommended. Acidity avoiders are better off buying a good conventional dark roast, which should display similarly low acidity along with a bit more flavor.
Those acidity-avoiders who can put up with a smoky, dullish, though reasonably nuanced and full-bodied cup with very low, measurably low, acidity.
An ultra-dark roast that preserves some pleasing chocolate character amid the smoky embers. Low in acidity, both perceived and measured.
Robust, dark-chocolaty cup for acidity-avoiders.
A pungently authoritative but cleanly refined Sumatra in a tactfully darker-roasted style.
Crisp rather than bright. An excellent choice for those who enjoy a quietly complex medium-roasted coffee with natural sweetness and low acidity.
The combination of sweetness and austere beauty characteristic of the finest Kenyas displays in this exceptional coffee.

Coffee Origin: Ka'u growing district, southwestern corner of the "Big Island" of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: A dried-in-the-fruit coffee for purists: sweetly opulent yet cleanly bright.

Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Refreshing and exceptional in its delicate complexity, an orchard-like purity that could contrast with a rich dessert or brighten a light lunch. Don’t think about putting anything into it except your lips.

Coffee Origin: San Pedro Necta, Huehuetenango growing region, Guatemala.
Bottom Line: Fine choice for those who prefer depth, resonance and natural sweetness in a brewed coffee.
Those who like their dry, briskly bright cup nuanced with fruit and natural sweetness.

This intriguing variation on the dry-processed Ethiopia cup brings flowers and a fat, low-acid tropical fruit character forward, making it a good choice for those coffee lovers who pursue the exotic and different.
Balance without boredom in a lively, lighter-roasted cup.
Delicate yet rich acidity in a gentle, floral-toned version of the great Kenya profile.

Coffee Name: Peru La Prosperidad Special Reserve Fair Trade
Bottom Line: Enjoy this quiet, melodious coffee as you contemplate the complex and inspiring relationship it represents between you, the green buyers and roasters who live in the mountains of Vermont, and the farmer producers who live far in the remote mountains of northern Peru.
Those looking for a dependable, balanced morning cup. Classic and understated.
Those drawn to the simultaneously elegant and exotic. Pleasing when taken with whitener, but at its dramatic best black.

Coffee Name: Ka’u Coffee Natural Dried Red Caturra
Coffee Origin: Ka'u growing district, southwestern corner of the "Big Island" of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Those who want to sample a quieter, cleaner version of the typically lushly fruity but often fermenty dried-in-the-fruit, “natural”-processed cup.

Coffee Name: Honduras Finca El Gringacho Yellow Catuai
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy a crisp cup with impressive tart-to-sweet balance and lemony-cocoa aromatics.
A sensitively light-roasted, pleasing version of the rare, giant-beaned Maragogipe.
Those who enjoy crisp, fruit-toned white wines. Displays a hint of the elegantly dry, pungent fruit sensation associated with the Bourbon variety from which Pacas mutated.
Delicate yet intense, this is an unusual, perhaps extreme, version of the already distinctive lemon and floral wet-processed Yirgacheffe profile.

Coffee Origin: Horqueta, Volcan growing region, western Panama.
Bottom Line: Paradoxical excitement – honeyish sweetness supporting dry, tart fruit – in a lightish-roasted version of the celebrated Geisha variety.
Those who enjoy the sweet fruit, brandy and pungent aromatic wood character typical of the best dried-in-the-fruit coffees. Rather light-roasted, but sensitively so.
Overall complexity and balance could make this selection an interesting starter dried-in-the-fruit coffee for purists who are tempted to stray from their clean and classic wet-processed habits.

Coffee Name: El Salvado Finca Ayatepeque Natural-Processed Pacamara
Bottom Line: An impressively clean, fresh-toned version of the big, complex fruit character associated with dried-in-the-fruit coffees. The subtly distinctive and complex Pacamara varietal character doubtless also contributes to this coffee’s distinction.

Exemplary example of the balanced, round, quietly deep-toned cup for which Nicaragua is particularly admired. Perhaps the finely balanced acidity and complex aromatics can be attributed to the heirloom Bourbon cultivar.
Those who enjoy a pure, soft yet intense, meadowy breakfast cup.
Unusual and distinctive profile, with the savory/sweet complexity found in the best of any given year’s Pacamara. Should please both coffee adventurers and purists. Very sensitively roasted.

Those who enjoy the sweet and avoid the bitter in coffee and life. A coffee almost shocking in its natural sweetness. This is not the empty sweetness of refined sugar but rather of ripe fruit, floral honey and fresh-cut, aromatic wood.
A Colombia of the true, good old school: Pure and brightly acidy yet accessibly syrupy and sweet-toned.

Coffee Name: Kenya Nyeri AB Gichatha-ini Signature Series
Bottom Line: An almost transcendent expression of one of the world’s finest coffee types.
Those looking for excitement. Almost startling intensity and complexity in this unusually clean, bright Harrar.
Only masochists. Our November 2011 supermarket sampling suggests better Robusta-heavy nationally branded canned blends are available at a comparable price.

For the curious, an object lesson in how bad a coffee can get if it fails to be developed in the roast. Could perhaps be seen as a botched exercise in anti-Starbuckism, a coffee as raw and woody as many Starbucks coffees are close to burned.
The organic seal is impressive even though the cup isn’t.
A particularly bad dark-roasted Colombia at the tail end of a bad year for Colombias generally.
Least offensive of the canned Robusta-centered supermarket blends tested for our November 2011 cupping.
Lovers of very delicate drip coffee.
Those on a budget looking for a modest, balanced rendition of a classic American breakfast cup.
An almost transcendently classic coffee in the depth and range of its sensation, intense yet balanced.
Those who have learned to enjoy lighter-roasted coffees that bring the freshness of the coffee flower and fruit to the cup.
This dramatic expression of the citrus and floral Ethiopia cup should please those who enjoy spicy, complex dry white table wines.
Lovers of bright, delicate white table wines and coffee drinkers who enjoy the citrus and floral character of washed Ethiopia Yirgacheffe coffees.
Those who enjoy a bright but balanced, intensely fragrant breakfast cup.
Fine example of a dried-in-the-fruit coffee, lushly yet freshly fruit-toned.

A fine coffee for anyone or any occasion, but aficionados may particularly enjoy attempting to pick out the interwoven contributions of the three processing methods. The brandyish dried-in-the-fruit component is easiest to detect.

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia Region, Sidama Province, Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: A dried-in-the-fruit coffee with rugged presence and big body that should please those who enjoy slightly edgy spirits: peaty single malts, the more rustic tequilas.
Extravagant, high-toned and intense; should particularly please lovers of dry, spicy white table wines and perfumy gins.
Richness and complexity in a darker roasted classic coffee.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Export Reserve, Light Roast
Bottom Line: Although a light roast in indicated on the packaging, by international standards this is a medium-dark roast, appealing to those who enjoy the slightly smoky, chocolaty character applied to a fine high-grown coffee by medium-dark roasting.
Well-balanced and distinctive with the complexity of the best Kenya coffees - 95 points, October 2011.
The aromatic fireworks of a fine dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia with none of the fermenty downside. Splendid coffee.
The Sumatra earth and fruit character is a bit over the top here but most people who buy Sumatras are looking for energy over elegance anyhow.
A dried-in-the-fruit coffee that walks on the wild side, with a fermenty, alcoholic sweetness that conveys considerable complexity as well as a faint overripe, composty shadow.
A style of coffee we used to call “after-dinner,” meaning it embodies an arm-chair-and-brandy sort of richness and authority.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Those coffee drinkers who avoid aggressive acidity and enjoy dark chocolate and nut nuance.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Finca Santa Lucia Organic
Bottom Line: Classic in its bright acidity; unusual in its rather deep, peach-and-melon fruit.

Coffee Name: Guatemala Quiche Chajulense Fair Trade Organic
Bottom Line: Lovers of red table wines that pleasingly balance fruit and oak.

Coffee Name: Ethiopia Sidama Union Fair Trade Organic
Bottom Line: Pure, crisply floral and citrus wet-processed Ethiopia of the classic style with Fair-Trade/organic credentials.

Coffee Name: Café Tierra Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Fair Trade Organic
Bottom Line: Quietly distinctive Yirgacheffe should please lovers of classic coffees without alarming them with excessive aromatic fireworks.

Coffee Name: Organic Ethiopia Worka Coop Natural Process
Bottom Line: Those who want difference and drama in their cup.

Coffee Name: Organic Costa Rica Las Lajas Natural Process
Bottom Line: Naturally sweet but crisply nuanced, a coffee for lovers of soft, subtly complex white table wines.
One of the world’s most distinctive origins in a darker-roasted mode.
Solidly satisfying breakfast cup with a quiet, tartly rich complexity associated with cultivars derived from the heirloom Bourbon variety of Arabica, in this case, Pacas.
Refreshing coffee; think the sweet, pink sort of grapefruit with deepening resonances of cedar and dark chocolate.
An acidity-lover’s coffee for sure, its grandly expressed brightness intensified by an unusually light roast.

Coffee Name: Kenya Thika Chania Estate Natural Process
Bottom Line: Lovers of big, fruity red table wines and those coffee drinkers who already know they enjoy the lushly fruit- and brandy-toned character of a lightly fermented dried-in-the-fruit “natural” coffee.
An almost creamily smooth mouthfeel and quiet, relatively restrained acidity makes this a particularly accessible rendition of the celebrated Kenya profile.
Those who prefer the delicately refreshing possibilities of the Kenya profile.
Intense but sweetly nuanced acidity should please those who enjoy a bright but engagingly complex cup.
The Kenya acidity is enveloped in rich, brandyish fruit and cocoa notes, making this a Kenya for lovers of fruit-rich red table wines.
Those who enjoy a bracing, complex acidy sensation without a hint of sour bite; the acidity is wine-like and nuanced with pungent cedar and lush night flowers.
A slightly bitterish but pleasing bite gives authority to this richly classic Kenya with its spicy floral and pungent berry notes.

Coffee Name: Kenya AA Kiaora Estate Full City Roast
Bottom Line: Distinctive Kenya fruit in a superbly balanced, versatile cup.
A balanced and complete medium-roasted cup, yet remarkable in its aromatic detail.
A brightly acidy coffee with complete and seductive balance and delicately distinctive, layered Kenya aromatics.
A distinctive and intense yet balanced expression of the pungent/sweet fruit-toned Kenya character.
Lovers of bright, dry white wines and coffee lovers interested in an engaging variation on the classic Kenya profile.

Coffee Name: La Union Mexico Fair Trade Organic
Bottom Line: Balanced Latin-American-style breakfast cup, sweetly crisp and fruit-toned with a hint of savory depth and solid social and environmental credentials.
Heavy body and rich acidity in particular should help flavor pair with sweetener and/or whitener.
Presumably the influence of the Bourbon cultivar gives the fruit its pungent, roundly tart, raisiny richness here. Should please those who enjoy red table wines with dry, complex fruit character.
Wonderfully summery breakfast cup.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Finca Los Alpes Tierra Fertil Pacamara
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy sensory distinction without acidy drama.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Finca Los Alpes El Banco Pacamara
Bottom Line: Lovers of decisively dry but complexly aromatic white table wines should enjoy this very light-roasted coffee.
Superb, sweetly earthy, resoundingly complex Sumatra for those who already love Sumatras and want to move up, or those who have never sampled the type and want to at its best.
Nicely balances the deep, rustic fruit of classic Indonesia coffees with a brighter Central America.
Those whose associations with autumn include the sweetly pungent, slightly smoky, deep, resonant.

Coffee Name: Colombia Cup of Excellence 2011 First Place Winner
Coffee Origin: San Agustín growing region, Huila Department, southern Colombia
Bottom Line: Those who want to enjoy the assertively acidy but balanced and complexly nuanced cup that impresses international juries.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Las Lajas Honey Process
Bottom Line: Low-toned complexity, smoothly lively mouthfeel and easy, approachable acidity should make this a comfortable but engaging breakfast cup.
Pronounced but balanced acidity and complex, harmonious aromatics in a classic medium-roasted Antigua.

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing district, northern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: A superb Sumatra; a wonderful introduction to this unorthodox type for those who don’t know it and a revelation for those who only know the sharply musty variety.

Coffee Origin: Tarrazu growing region, central Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Bright, sweetly acidy and resoundingly complex straight shot; sweet and gently chocolaty in short milk. Not a caffè latte or long milk espresso.
This unusual coffee should please those who find many admired coffees too acidy and intense, but who still enjoy distinction and originality.
Those who prefer quiet depth to bright acidity with a bonus of impressive social and environmental credentials.
Those who enjoy grandly acidy, big-bodied medium-roasted coffees.
Light roasting develops the floral sweetness of this pure and delicate coffee.
Both those who have never sampled a brandyish, fruity style natural coffee or those who have and love them.
Those who prefer balance to intensity; smooth is perhaps the most overused word in beverage description, but this coffee defines it.

Coffee Origin: Matagalpa and Jinotega growing regions, Nicaragua
Bottom Line: Exemplary Nicaragua: rich, robust, deep-toned.

Coffee Name: Kenya Kagumo PB Special Reserve Micro Lot
Bottom Line: Crisp, cleanly bright breakfast cup with a complicating hint of East Africa.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Micro Lot “Pepe” Honey Processed
Bottom Line: A grandly classic Latin-American cup: powerful but nuanced acidity, full mouthfeel, deeply expressed aromatics.

Coffee Name: Costa Rica Finca Las Gravileas Fair Trade Organic
Coffee Origin: Tarrazu growing region, central Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy sensory depth and quiet authority. Rich and balanced when taken black, but should handle whitener well.
Clarity and balance in a crisp morning cup.
The pungent Kenya fruit is gently deepened by the roast, rounding complexity and softening acidity.
The pungent Kenya fruit is softened and deepened without loss of its tart authority in this quietly complex version of the Kenya profile.

Coffee Name: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Koke Coop Fair Trade Organic
Bottom Line: Delicately pure coffee, light-roasted to develop fresh, orchard-like aromatics and natural sweetness. Excellent environmental and social credentials.

Coffee Name: Nicaragua Cinco De Junio Fair Trade Organic
Bottom Line: Crisp, sweet-toned lighter-roasted coffee with fine floral notes and excellent environmental and social credentials.

Coffee Origin: Volcán growing region, west and southwest of Volcán Barú, western Panama.
Bottom Line: Coffee lovers with who don’t mind dropping significant money on a memorable version of the rare and celebrated Gesha profile
Elegantly pungent and earthy, a good choice for those who enjoy fine Sumatras.
Those in quest of the quiet, resonant side of the celebrated Kenya profile.
Deep, tartly rich cup should please those who enjoy dry, complex red table wines.
Those who enjoy intense, challenging, strong-charactered beverages.
Classically bright and balanced breakfast cup with impressive social and environmental credentials.
Lovers of dark roasts that combine crisp, roasty character with a full range of flavor and aromatics.
Dark-roast fans who don’t need pronounced bitterness to convince them they’re drinking coffee. Displays solid dark-roast character while retaining sweetness and some Kenya complexity.

A fine, balanced Yirgacheffe with muted aromatics. A good choice perhaps for those who find the lemon and flowers of most Yirgacheffes too brightly distracting and who may prefer a quieter, rounder version of the type with a fuller, more syrupy feel on the palate.
Dark-roast Sumatra lovers, of which there are many. This version has less musty-earthiness and more chocolate than most traditional Sumatras.
A smooth, nut-and-chocolate-toned option for those who avoid brighter, more acidy coffees.
Those who enjoy classically delicate light-roasted coffees, complex and lively.
Those who enjoy a straightforward, briskly medium-roasted Yirgacheffe cup: silky, floral, lemony.
Those who enjoy their lemony Yirgacheffe with an overlay of tactful roastiness and impressive social and environmental credentials.
Should appeal to lovers of dry, complex white wines.
Those who prefer an Ethiopia that minimizes delicate floral character in favor of crisp, lemony authority.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
Bottom Line: Ethiopia flowers, lemon and cocoa nuance in a complex, bright but sweetly balanced cup.
A traditional style Mexico coffee, balanced and chocolate-nut toned. Should satisfy those breakfast-cuppers who prefer round and caramelly to bright and fruit-toned.
Simply a superb coffee, as grand as it is balanced and inviting, as fine with milk as it is black.
Quiet authority in a gently complex, cocoa-toned Guatemala.
Those who enjoy dry, delicate, minerally white table wines.
Black coffee drinkers who prefer subtlety to drama.

Coffee Origin: Tarrazu growing region, central Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Those who prefer depth to brightness in a crisp but comfortable breakfast cup.
The great Gesha profile pure and uncompromised. Too intense and distinctive not to mention too expensive for many coffee drinkers, but try it at least once.
An exquisitely balanced Yirgacheffe, free of lemon zest intensity or over-the-top flowers yet still distinctive and unmistakable in its Yirgacheffe character.
Those who favor a medium-roasted cup with discreet fruit notes, balance and sweetness.
Elegant yet uncompromising in its Sumatra-ness, should appeal to lovers of the origin as well as making a good starter Sumatra for those purists resistant to the style.
Fans of the deep and resonant style in Latin American coffees.
Delicate, pure, gently bright; classic breakfast cup.

Coffee Origin: Aceh growing region, northwestern Indonesia, Indonesia.
Bottom Line: Superbly elegant interpretation of the Sumatra earth and fruit profile.
Anyone who loves coffee, but particularly those interested in exploring the subtle but distinctive aromatics of the finest of Guatemala coffees.
A Kenya for those who value great natural sweetness, thoroughly engaging complexity and silky refinement.
Finely balanced Africa Bourbon-style cup, without the aromatic intensity of a fine Kenya yet poised and resonant.
Impressive balance and completeness in a fine Latin-American style breakfast cup.
Those who enjoy fragrant but dry white table wines.
Sensory adventurers. An exotic, ambiguous coffee with great fundamental sweetness and much, too much perhaps, going on aromatically. Definitely not for the purist.
A nicely balanced East Africa cup, gentle, quietly complex, with a hint of Kenya black-currant richness.
Not intense, but many coffee drinkers may prefer it that way. Soft, balanced, sweet-citrus-toned.
A gentle, balanced version of the Africa Bourbon cup.
Not for the timid. Lovers of sweet citrus, flowers and powerful acidity.
Delicacy and depth in a gentle dark-roasted cup.
Offers a gentle cup with deep complexity.
Offers depth, balance and considerable low-key nuance.

Simply a splendid coffee, complete, majestic, powerful but gracious, meaning even those who avoid big, assertive lighter-roasted coffees should respond to this one for its sweetness, depth and balance.
Intensely aromatic, award-winning coffee.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, "Big Island" of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Graceful, fruit-toned, easy-drinking Kona.
Balance, delicacy and notes of lemon and cocoa in an award-winning coffee.
Those who enjoy a naturally sweet, round, cherryish-fruit- and nut-toned cup.
Balance and complexity in an outstanding Bolivia.
Classic Latin American cup: Nothing is excessive or out of balance; nothing essential is missing.

Coffee Name: Extra Fancy Kona Coffee Medium Roast
Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Aficionados interested in a coffee with a depth and range of aromatic expression that seems to define an almost singular sensory niche, brighter than Sumatra but deeper than East Africa.

Coffee Origin: Waghi Valley, Western Highlands, Papua New Guinea.
Bottom Line: Refreshing, edge-of-the-woods aromatics, clean but complex.

Coffee Origin: Kainantu district, Eastern Highlands Province, Papua New Guinea.
Bottom Line: Quietly exotic, balanced, soft, exceptional.
Rich, shifting complexity should please those who like oak-and-fruit dominated red table wines.

Coffee Name: Organic Costa Rica La Amistad Estate
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy crisp, dry white table wines.
Flowers and pungent, grapefruity citrus in a fine, balanced Africa coffee.
Intense fruit- and chocolate-toned cup.
Impressive natural sweetness and intense, complex aroma.
Lovers of complexly bright, citrusy coffees.
A syrupy, savory-sweet fruit and rich complexity makes this a fine candidate for an afternoon or after dinner coffee, while the large, bold Pacamara beans are nice for coffee show and tell.
Those who appreciate effortless grace.
A fine rendition of the classic American breakfast blend: sweetly tart, refreshing.
Light-footed complexity in a classic Yirgacheffe.
Aficionados interested in the unusual honey process, and anyone interested in a gently bright, lemony cup.

Coffee Origin: Tres Rios growing region, Costa Rica
Bottom Line: Citrusy excitement in this lighter roasted Costa Rica.

Coffee Name: Guatemala Antigua La Flor del Cafe
Bottom Line: A medium-dark roast softens the fruit and develops the chocolate in this quiet, balanced Antigua.

Coffee Name: Colombia Jardin Finca El Boton Maragogype Peaberry
Bottom Line: An opportunity to sample a specially graded, unique variety of arabica with a rather unusual malty, woody character.

Coffee Origin: Fazenda Cachoeira da Grama, Mogiana Region, Brazil.
Bottom Line: Although evaluated as a standard brewed coffee, this blend displays the rounded acidity, full body and aromatic wood notes that play well in espresso brewing.
Sweet but tartly pungent cup.
Dramatic aroma in this exotic but balanced variation on the traditional Mocha Java blend.
A fine Brazil Mogiana in the classic natural style. Those who find most fine coffees too sharply bright should particularly enjoy this one.
Classic Sumatra aromatics in a tactful dark roast: A grapefruit-like citrus enlivens earth and fir.

Coffee Origin: Alajuela growing region, central Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: Aficionados interested in dried-in the-fruit coffee, an unusual process for Costa Rica, and anyone interested in a deep, balanced cup.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, "Big Island" of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Sweetness, fruit and spice from the famous Kona growing region.

Roaster Name: Conservatory for Coffee, Tea and Cocoa
Bottom Line: A finely balanced cup.
The glory of this coffee is an acidity as sweet, tart and refreshing as a spring morning. Everything else is pretty impressive as well.
A brisk version of the great Kenya profile.
A striking variation on the floral-toned East Africa cup. If you enjoy Yirgacheffe, try this Rwanda for a fine variant on the style.

Coffee Origin: Tarrazu growing region, central Costa Rica.
Bottom Line: An unusual processing method nets a distinctively rounded, nut-toned coffee of a style more associated with the best Brazils than with Costa Rica. A fine choice for those coffee drinkers who enjoy complexity but avoid intensely acidy or bright coffees.

Coffee Name: El Salvador La Pinera COE Lot 11
Bottom Line: An award winning, richly complex cup.
Spicy floral and soft fruit highlighted in this version of the Kenya profile.
Classic breakfast cup: sweetly brisk and fruit-toned with a kitchen-filling aroma.
A slightly darker-than-medium roast style seems to develop a resonant depth in this clean, straightforward Dominican coffee.
Refreshing, delicate, poised cup.
Remarkably refined, buoyantly and sweetly bright Kenya.
Lovers of fine dark beers.
Flowers without sentiment in a classic Yirgacheffe.
Those who can handle triumphant power and brightness.
A classic Antigua: Perfectly balanced structure under a veil of subtle aromatic nuance.
Those who enjoy lighter-roasted versions of the world’s great origins. The orangy citrus and rose notes should please everyone. The nut note may strike some as just a touch too raw.
A Yirgacheffe on the tart side with expressive aromatics and impressive social and environmental credentials.
A slow roast stretches and complicates the aromatic range of this classic wet-processed Ethiopia.
Less lemon and more aromatic wood and plummy fruit in this slightly darker-roasted, classic wet-processed Ethiopia.
A Yirgacheffe perhaps for those who prefer dry, minerally white table wines to sweeter, floral styles.
A very pure lighter-roasted Yirgacheffe directly expressing the orchardy freshness of coffee fruit and flower.
More chocolate than usual in this showy yet balanced Yirgacheffe.
Fine, lemon-toned Ethiopia with complex nuance and richly bracing acidity.
A crisply balanced Yirgacheffe for those who prefer flowers and fir to citrus and brightness.
The classic Yirgacheffe aromatic package: intense, complete, yet balanced.
An extraordinarily opulent and deep version of the great Yirgacheffe profile.

Coffee Origin: Toraja growing region, southwestern Sulawesi, Indonesia
Bottom Line: Unusual cup: heavy, gently pungent, sweet with a hint of savory.
An elegantly bright version of the Kenya profile.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, "Big Island" of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Exceptional Kona in which meticulous wet-processing preserves its lush delicacy.
An exhilarating and exceptional variant on the great Gesha cup for the well-heeled aficionado.
A worldwide voyage in this Kona blend.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Pacamara Finca Los Alpes The Bank
Bottom Line: Deep, slightly savory yet lushly floral, crisp and lemony, quietly exotic.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Yellow Bourbon Finca Los Alpes El Amarillo
Bottom Line: Deep, round, sweetly honeyish cup.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Bourbon Finca Los Alpes La Punta
Bottom Line: Refreshingly lively fruit- and floral-toned cup.
A moderately dark roast develops an attractively pungent, cedary fruit character.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Finca Los Planes Lote La Lagunita
Bottom Line: Those who enjoy the tart cherry and pungent berry character of a lighter-roasted coffee of the Bourbon variety, though this 2009 harvest is discreetly showing its age.

With its acidity perhaps muted by the months since the 2009 harvest but its subtly balanced citrus-through-chocolate character intact, a good choice for those who enjoy a complex, softly bright breakfast cup.
Balanced, quietly complete cup with complex, chocolate-leaning fruit character.
Refreshing, sweetly and impressively complex breakfast cup.
A well-rounded, sweetly balanced cup with complex fruit throughout.
An essay in elegant, complexly fruit-toned acidity.
Those who enjoy a sweet-toned, balanced cup with quiet depth and understated complexity.

Coffee Origin: Tarrazu growing region, central Costa Rica
Bottom Line: Purity and clarity without monotony for lovers of the classic American cup.

Coffee Origin: Tarrazu growing region, central Costa Rica
Bottom Line: Those who admire the delicately lemony, dry chocolate style of Central American cup.
Lovers of crisp, discreetly (and naturally) dark-chocolate-toned breakfast coffees.

Coffee Name: La Pira Costa Rica Geisha Natural
Bottom Line: A finely understated, silky light-roasted coffee with crisp nut and raisin character.

Coffee Name: El Salvador Santa Rita Bourbon Natural
Bottom Line: Aficionados may take interest in this particular incarnation of the pungent-sweet Bourbon character; less scholarly black coffee drinkers may simply enjoy the balanced, ripe sweetness the cup.
Those who avoid aggressively acidy coffees yet still value intensity in flavor and aromatics.
Those who particularly value depth and richness in a coffee, not to mention impressive social and environmental credentials.
Those who favor a crisp, complexly high-toned Ethiopian style breakfast coffee.

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, "Big Island" of Hawaii.
Bottom Line: Those in pursuit of an extremely rare coffee with great natural sweetness and delicate aromatic complexity.
Those who enjoy a gentle yet subtly exotic cup.
Those who enjoy fine red table wines that express restrained but complex fruit character.

Richly and roundly balanced, chocolate-toned cup.
